\n

\n \n England\n \n is a\n \n country\n \n that is\n \n part\n \n of the\n \n United Kingdom\n \n .\n \n \n [5]\n \n \n \n \n [6]\n \n \n \n \n [7]\n \n \n It shares land borders with\n \n Wales\n \n to the west and\n \n Scotland\n \n to the north-northwest. The\n \n Irish Sea\n \n lies west of England and the\n \n Celtic Sea\n \n lies to the southwest. England is separated from\n \n continental Europe\n \n by the\n \n North Sea\n \n to the east and the\n \n English Channel\n \n to the south. The country covers five-eighths of the island of\n \n Great Britain\n \n , which lies in the\n \n North Atlantic\n \n , and includes\n \n over 100 smaller islands\n \n , such as the\n \n Isles of Scilly\n \n and the\n \n Isle of Wight\n \n .\n

\n

\n The area now called England was first inhabited by modern humans during the\n \n Upper Palaeolithic\n \n period, but takes its name from the\n \n Angles\n \n , a\n \n Germanic\n \n tribe deriving its name from the\n \n Anglia\n \n peninsula, who settled during the 5th and 6th centuries. England became a unified state in the 10th century, and since the\n \n Age of Discovery\n \n , which began during the 15th century, has had a significant cultural and legal impact on the wider world.\n \n \n [8]\n \n \n The English language, the\n \n Anglican Church\n \n , and\n \n English law\n \n the basis for the\n \n common law\n \n legal systems of many other countries around the world developed in England, and the country\'s\n \n parliamentary system\n \n of government has been widely adopted by other nations.\n \n \n [9]\n \n \n The\n \n Industrial Revolution\n \n began in 18th-century England, transforming its society into the world\'s first industrialised nation.\n \n \n [10]\n \n \n

\n

\n England\'s terrain is chiefly low hills and\n \n plains\n \n , especially in central and southern England. However, there is upland and mountainous terrain in the north (for example, the\n \n Lake District\n \n and\n \n Pennines\n \n ) and in the west (for example,\n \n Dartmoor\n \n and the\n \n Shropshire Hills\n \n ). The capital is\n \n London\n \n , which has the largest metropolitan area in both the United Kingdom and the\n \n European Union\n \n .\n \n \n [nb 1]\n \n \n England\'s population of over 55million comprises 84% of the population of the United Kingdom,\n \n \n [3]\n \n \n largely concentrated around London, the\n \n South East\n \n , and conurbations in the\n \n Midlands\n \n , the\n \n North West\n \n , the\n \n North East\n \n , and\n \n Yorkshire\n \n , which each developed as major industrial regions during the 19th century.\n \n \n [11]\n \n \n

\n

\n The\n \n Kingdom of England\n \n which after 1535 included Wales ceased being a separate\n \n sovereign state\n \n on 1 May 1707, when the\n \n Acts of Union\n \n put into effect the terms agreed in the\n \n Treaty of Union\n \n the previous year, resulting in a political union with the\n \n Kingdom of Scotland\n \n to create the\n \n Kingdom of Great Britain\n \n .\n \n \n [12]\n \n \n \n \n [13]\n \n \n In 1801, Great Britain was united with the\n \n Kingdom of Ireland\n \n (through another\n \n Act of Union\n \n ) to become the\n \n United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland\n \n . In 1922 the\n \n Irish Free State\n \n seceded from the United Kingdom, leading to the latter being\n \n renamed\n \n the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland.\n

\n \n Toponymy\n \n \n \n

\n
\n See also:\n \n Toponymy of England\n \n
\n

\n The name "England" is derived from the\n \n Old English\n \n name\n \n Englaland\n \n , which means "land of the\n \n Angles\n \n ".\n \n \n [14]\n \n \n The Angles were one of the\n \n Germanic tribes\n \n that settled in Great Britain during the\n \n Early Middle Ages\n \n . The Angles came from the\n \n Anglia\n \n peninsula in the\n \n Bay of Kiel\n \n area (present-day German state of\n \n SchleswigHolstein\n \n ) of the\n \n Baltic Sea\n \n .\n \n \n [15]\n \n \n The earliest recorded use of the term, as "Engla londe", is in the late-ninth-century translation into\n \n Old English\n \n of\n \n Bede\n \n \'s\n \n \n Ecclesiastical History of the English People\n \n \n . The term was then used in a different sense to the modern one, meaning "the land inhabited by the English", and it included English people in what is now south-east Scotland but was then part of the English kingdom of\n \n Northumbria\n \n . The\n \n \n Anglo-Saxon Chronicle\n \n \n recorded that the\n \n Domesday Book\n \n of 1086 covered the whole of England, meaning the English kingdom, but a few years later the\n \n Chronicle\n \n stated that King\n \n Malcolm III\n \n went "out of Scotlande into\n \n Lothian\n \n in Englaland", thus using it in the more ancient sense.\n \n \n [16]\n \n \n According to the\n \n \n Oxford English Dictionary\n \n \n , its modern spelling was first used in 1538.\n \n \n [17]\n \n \n

\n

\n The earliest attested reference to the Angles occurs in the 1st-century work by\n \n Tacitus\n \n ,\n \n \n Germania\n \n \n , in which the\n \n Latin\n \n word\n \n Anglii\n \n is used.\n \n \n [18]\n \n \n The etymology of the tribal name itself is disputed by scholars; it has been suggested that it derives from the shape of the Angeln peninsula, an\n \n angular\n \n shape.\n \n \n [19]\n \n \n How and why a term derived from the name of a tribe that was less significant than others, such as the\n \n Saxons\n \n , came to be used for the entire country and its people is not known, but it seems this is related to the custom of calling the Germanic people in Britain\n \n Angli Saxones\n \n or English Saxons to distinguish them from continental Saxons (Eald-Seaxe) of Old Saxony between the Weser and Eider rivers in Northern Germany.\n \n \n [20]\n \n \n In\n \n Scottish Gaelic\n \n , another language which developed on the island of Great Britain, the Saxon tribe gave their name to the word for England (\n \n Sasunn\n \n );\n \n \n [21]\n \n \n similarly, the Welsh name for the English language is "\n \n Saesneg\n \n ".\n

\n

\n An alternative name for England is\n \n Albion\n \n . The name\n \n Albion\n \n originally referred to the entire island of Great Britain. The nominally earliest record of the name appears in the\n \n Aristotelian\n \n \n Corpus\n \n , specifically the 4th-century BC\n \n \n De Mundo\n \n \n :\n \n \n [22]\n \n \n "Beyond the\n \n Pillars of Hercules\n \n is the ocean that flows round the earth. In it are two very large islands called Britannia; these are Albion and\n \n Ierne\n \n ".\n \n \n [22]\n \n \n \n \n [23]\n \n \n But modern scholarly consensus ascribes\n \n De Mundo\n \n not to\n \n Aristotle\n \n but to\n \n Pseudo-Aristotle\n \n , i.e. it was written later in the\n \n Graeco-Roman\n \n period or afterwards. The word\n \n Albion\n \n () or\n \n insula Albionum\n \n has two possible origins. It either derives from a cognate of the Latin\n \n albus\n \n meaning white, a reference to the\n \n white cliffs of Dover\n \n (the only part of Britain visible from the European mainland)\n \n \n [24]\n \n \n or from the phrase the "island of the\n \n Albiones\n \n "\n \n \n [25]\n \n \n in the now lost\n \n \n Massaliote Periplus\n \n \n , that is attested through\n \n Avienus\n \n \'\n \n Ora Maritima\n \n \n \n [26]\n \n \n to which the former presumably served as a source.\n \n Albion\n \n is now applied to England in a more poetic capacity.\n \n \n [27]\n \n \n Another romantic name for England is\n \n Loegria\n \n , related to the\n \n Welsh\n \n word for England,\n \n Lloegr\n \n , and made popular by its use in\n \n Arthurian legend\n \n .\n

\n

\n \n History\n \n

\n
\n Main article:\n \n History of England\n \n
\n

\n \n Prehistory and antiquity\n \n

\n
\n Main article:\n \n Prehistoric Britain\n \n
\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n \n
\n \n Stonehenge\n \n , a\n \n Neolithic\n \n monument\n
\n
\n
\n

\n The earliest known evidence of human presence in the area now known as England was that of\n \n \n Homo antecessor\n \n \n , dating to approximately 780,000 years ago. The oldest proto-human bones discovered in England date from 500,000years ago.\n \n \n [28]\n \n \n Modern humans are known to have inhabited the area during the\n \n Upper Paleolithic\n \n period, though permanent settlements were only established within the last 6,000 years.\n \n \n [29]\n \n \n \n \n [30]\n \n \n After the last\n \n ice age\n \n only large mammals such as\n \n mammoths\n \n ,\n \n bison\n \n and\n \n woolly rhinoceros\n \n remained. Roughly 11,000years ago, when the\n \n ice sheets\n \n began to recede, humans repopulated the area; genetic research suggests they came from the northern part of the\n \n Iberian Peninsula\n \n .\n \n \n [31]\n \n \n The sea level was lower than now and Britain was connected by\n \n land bridge\n \n to Ireland and\n \n Eurasia\n \n .\n \n \n [32]\n \n \n As the seas rose, it was separated from Ireland 10,000years ago and from Eurasia two millennia later.\n

\n

\n The\n \n Beaker culture\n \n arrived around 2,500BC, introducing drinking and food vessels constructed from clay, as well as vessels used as reduction pots to smelt copper ores.\n \n \n [33]\n \n \n It was during this time that major\n \n Neolithic\n \n monuments such as\n \n Stonehenge\n \n and\n \n Avebury\n \n were constructed. By heating together tin and copper, which were in abundance in the area, the Beaker culture people made\n \n bronze\n \n , and later iron from iron ores. The development of iron\n \n smelting\n \n allowed the construction of better\n \n ploughs\n \n , advancing agriculture (for instance, with\n \n Celtic fields\n \n ), as well as the production of more effective weapons.\n \n \n [34]\n \n \n

\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n \n
\n \n Boudica\n \n led an uprising against the\n \n Roman Empire\n \n
\n
\n
\n

\n During the\n \n Iron Age\n \n ,\n \n Celtic culture\n \n , deriving from the\n \n Hallstatt\n \n and\n \n La Tne cultures\n \n , arrived from Central Europe.\n \n Brythonic\n \n was the spoken language during this time. Society was tribal; according to\n \n Ptolemy\n \n \'s\n \n \n Geographia\n \n \n there were around 20 tribes in the area. Earlier divisions are unknown because the Britons were not literate. Like other regions on the edge of the Empire, Britain had long enjoyed trading links with the Romans. Julius Caesar of the\n \n Roman Republic\n \n attempted to\n \n invade twice\n \n in 55BC; although largely unsuccessful, he managed to set up a\n \n client king\n \n from the\n \n Trinovantes\n \n .\n

\n

\n The Romans invaded Britain in 43 AD during the reign of Emperor\n \n Claudius\n \n , subsequently\n \n conquering much of Britain\n \n , and the area was incorporated into the Roman Empire as\n \n Britannia province\n \n .\n \n \n [35]\n \n \n The best-known of the native tribes who attempted to resist were the\n \n Catuvellauni\n \n led by\n \n Caratacus\n \n . Later, an uprising led by\n \n Boudica\n \n , Queen of the\n \n Iceni\n \n , ended with Boudica\'s suicide following her defeat at the\n \n Battle of Watling Street\n \n .\n \n \n [36]\n \n \n The author of one study of Roman Britain suggested that from 43 AD to 84 AD, the Roman invaders killed somewhere between 100,000 and 250,000 people from a population of perhaps 2,000,000.\n \n \n [37]\n \n \n This era saw a\n \n Greco-Roman\n \n culture prevail with the introduction of\n \n Roman law\n \n ,\n \n Roman architecture\n \n ,\n \n aqueducts\n \n ,\n \n sewers\n \n , many agricultural items and silk.\n \n \n [38]\n \n \n \n \n [39]\n \n \n \n \n [40]\n \n \n In the 3rd century, Emperor\n \n Septimius Severus\n \n died at\n \n Eboracum\n \n (now\n \n York\n \n ), where\n \n Constantine\n \n was subsequently proclaimed emperor.\n \n \n [41]\n \n \n

\n

\n There is debate about when Christianity was first introduced; it was no later than the 4th century, probably much earlier. According to\n \n Bede\n \n , missionaries were sent from Rome by\n \n Eleutherius\n \n at the request of the chieftain\n \n Lucius of Britain\n \n in 180 AD, to settle differences as to Eastern and Western ceremonials, which were disturbing the church. There are traditions linked to Glastonbury claiming an introduction through\n \n Joseph of Arimathea\n \n , while others claim through\n \n Lucius of Britain\n \n .\n \n \n [42]\n \n \n By 410, during the\n \n Decline of the Roman Empire\n \n , Britain was left exposed by the\n \n end of Roman rule in Britain\n \n and the withdrawal of Roman army units, to defend the frontiers in continental Europe and partake in civil wars.\n \n \n [43]\n \n \n Celtic Christian monastic and missionary movements flourished:\n \n Patrick\n \n (5th-century Ireland) and in the 6th century Brendan (Clonfert), Comgall (Bangor), David (Wales), Aiden (Lindisfarne) and Columba (Iona). This period of Christianity was influenced by ancient Celtic culture in its sensibilities, polity, practices and theology. Local "congregations" were centred in the monastic community and monastic leaders were more like chieftains, as peers, rather than in the more hierarchical system of the Roman-dominated church.\n \n \n [44]\n \n \n

\n
\n
\n

\n \n Middle Ages\n \n

\n
\n Main article:\n \n England in the Middle Ages\n \n
\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n \n
\n Replica of the 7th-century ceremonial\n \n Sutton Hoo helmet\n \n from the\n \n Kingdom of East Anglia\n \n
\n
\n
\n

\n \n Roman military\n \n withdrawals left Britain open to invasion by pagan, seafaring warriors from north-western continental Europe, chiefly the Saxons,\n \n Angles\n \n ,\n \n Jutes\n \n and Frisians who had long raided the coasts of the Roman province and began to settle, initially in the eastern part of the country.\n \n \n [43]\n \n \n Their advance was contained for some decades after the Britons\' victory at the\n \n Battle of Mount Badon\n \n , but subsequently resumed, over-running the fertile lowlands of Britain and reducing the area under\n \n Brythonic\n \n control to a series of separate enclaves in the more rugged country to the west by the end of the 6th century. Contemporary texts describing this period are extremely scarce, giving rise to its description as a\n \n Dark Age\n \n . The nature and progression of the\n \n Anglo-Saxon settlement of Britain\n \n is consequently subject to considerable disagreement. Roman-dominated Christianity had, in general, disappeared from the conquered territories, but was reintroduced by missionaries from Rome led by\n \n Augustine\n \n from 597 onwards.\n \n \n [45]\n \n \n Disputes between the Roman- and Celtic-dominated forms of Christianity ended in victory for the Roman tradition at the\n \n Council of Whitby\n \n (664), which was ostensibly about haircuts and the date of Easter, but more significantly, about the differences in Roman and Celtic forms of authority, theology, and practice (Lehane).\n

\n

\n During the settlement period the lands ruled by the incomers seem to have been fragmented into numerous tribal territories, but by the 7th century, when substantial evidence of the situation again becomes available, these had coalesced into roughly a dozen kingdoms including\n \n Northumbria\n \n ,\n \n Mercia\n \n ,\n \n Wessex\n \n ,\n \n East Anglia\n \n ,\n \n Essex\n \n ,\n \n Kent\n \n and\n \n Sussex\n \n . Over the following centuries, this process of political consolidation continued.\n \n \n [46]\n \n \n The 7th century saw a struggle for hegemony between Northumbria and Mercia, which in the 8th century gave way to Mercian preeminence.\n \n \n [47]\n \n \n In the early 9th century Mercia was displaced as the foremost kingdom by Wessex. Later in that century escalating attacks by the\n \n Danes\n \n culminated in the conquest of the north and east of England, overthrowing the kingdoms of Northumbria, Mercia and East Anglia. Wessex under\n \n Alfred the Great\n \n was left as the only surviving English kingdom, and under his successors, it steadily expanded at the expense of the kingdoms of the\n \n Danelaw\n \n . This brought about the political unification of England, first accomplished under\n \n thelstan\n \n in 927 and definitively established after further conflicts by\n \n Eadred\n \n in 953. A fresh wave of Scandinavian attacks from the late 10th century ended with the conquest of this united kingdom by\n \n Sweyn Forkbeard\n \n in 1013 and again by his son\n \n Cnut\n \n in 1016, turning it into the centre of a short-lived\n \n North Sea Empire\n \n that also included\n \n Denmark\n \n and\n \n Norway\n \n . However, the native royal dynasty was restored with the accession of\n \n Edward the Confessor\n \n in 1042.\n

\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n \n
\n \n King Henry V\n \n at the\n \n Battle of Agincourt\n \n , fought on\n \n Saint Crispin\n \n \'s Day and concluded with an English victory against a larger French army in the\n \n Hundred Years\' War\n \n
\n
\n
\n

\n A dispute over the succession to Edward led to the\n \n Norman conquest of England\n \n in 1066, accomplished by an army led by\n \n Duke William of Normandy\n \n .\n \n \n [48]\n \n \n The\n \n Normans\n \n themselves originated from\n \n Scandinavia\n \n and had settled in Normandy in the late 9th and early 10th centuries.\n \n \n [49]\n \n \n This conquest led to the almost total dispossession of the English elite and its replacement by a new French-speaking aristocracy, whose speech had a profound and permanent effect on the English language.\n \n \n [50]\n \n \n

\n

\n Subsequently, the\n \n House of Plantagenet\n \n from Anjou inherited the English throne under\n \n Henry II\n \n , adding England to the budding\n \n Angevin Empire\n \n of fiefs the family had inherited in France including\n \n Aquitaine\n \n .\n \n \n [51]\n \n \n They reigned for three centuries, some noted monarchs being\n \n Richard I\n \n ,\n \n Edward I\n \n ,\n \n Edward III\n \n and\n \n Henry V\n \n .\n \n \n [51]\n \n \n The period saw changes in trade and legislation, including the signing of the\n \n \n Magna Carta\n \n \n , an English legal charter used to limit the sovereign\'s powers by law and protect the privileges of freemen. Catholic\n \n monasticism\n \n flourished, providing philosophers, and the universities of Oxford and Cambridge were founded with royal patronage. The\n \n Principality of Wales\n \n became a Plantagenet fief during the 13th century\n \n \n [52]\n \n \n and the\n \n Lordship of Ireland\n \n was given to the English monarchy by the Pope.\n

\n

\n During the 14th century, the Plantagenets and the\n \n House of Valois\n \n both claimed to be legitimate claimants to the\n \n House of Capet\n \n and with it France; the two powers clashed in the\n \n Hundred Years\' War\n \n .\n \n \n [53]\n \n \n The\n \n Black Death\n \n epidemic\n \n hit England\n \n ; starting in 1348, it eventually killed up to half of England\'s\n \n inhabitants\n \n .\n \n \n [54]\n \n \n \n \n [55]\n \n \n From 1453 to 1487 civil war occurred between two branches of the royal family the\n \n Yorkists\n \n and\n \n Lancastrians\n \n known as the\n \n Wars of the Roses\n \n .\n \n \n [56]\n \n \n Eventually it led to the Yorkists losing the throne entirely to a Welsh noble family the\n \n Tudors\n \n , a branch of the Lancastrians headed by\n \n Henry Tudor\n \n who invaded with Welsh and Breton mercenaries, gaining victory at the\n \n Battle of Bosworth Field\n \n where the Yorkist king\n \n Richard III\n \n was killed.\n \n \n [57]\n \n \n

\n

\n \n Early modern\n \n

\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n \n
\n \n King Henry VIII\n \n became\n \n Supreme Head of the Church of England\n \n
\n
\n
\n

\n During the\n \n Tudor period\n \n , the\n \n Renaissance\n \n reached England through Italian courtiers, who reintroduced artistic, educational and scholarly debate from classical antiquity.\n \n \n [58]\n \n \n England began to develop\n \n naval skills\n \n , and exploration to the West intensified.\n \n \n [59]\n \n \n \n \n [60]\n \n \n

\n

\n \n Henry VIII\n \n broke from communion with the Catholic Church, over issues relating to his divorce, under the\n \n Acts of Supremacy\n \n in 1534 which proclaimed the monarch head of the\n \n Church of England\n \n . In contrast with much of European Protestantism, the\n \n roots of the split\n \n were more political than theological.\n \n \n [nb 2]\n \n \n He also legally incorporated his ancestral land Wales into the Kingdom of England with the\n \n 15351542 acts\n \n . There were internal religious conflicts during the reigns of Henry\'s daughters,\n \n Mary I\n \n and\n \n Elizabeth I\n \n . The former took the country back to Catholicism while the latter broke from it again, forcefully asserting the supremacy of\n \n Anglicanism\n \n .\n

\n

\n Competing with\n \n Spain\n \n , the first English colony in the Americas was founded in 1585 by explorer\n \n Walter Raleigh\n \n in\n \n Virginia\n \n and named\n \n Roanoke\n \n . The Roanoke colony failed and is known as the lost colony after it was found abandoned on the return of the late-arriving supply ship.\n \n \n [62]\n \n \n With the\n \n East India Company\n \n , England also competed with the\n \n Dutch\n \n and\n \n French\n \n in the East. During the\n \n Elizabethan period\n \n , England was at war with Spain. An\n \n armada\n \n sailed from Spain in 1588 as part of a wider plan to invade England and re-establish a Catholic monarchy. The plan was thwarted by bad coordination, stormy weather and successful harrying attacks by an English fleet under\n \n Lord Howard of Effingham\n \n . This failure did not end the threat: Spain launched two further armadas, in\n \n 1596\n \n and\n \n 1597\n \n , but both were driven back by storms. The political structure of the island changed in 1603, when the\n \n King of Scots\n \n ,\n \n James VI\n \n , a kingdom which had been a long-time rival to English interests, inherited the throne of England as\n \n James I\n \n , thereby creating a\n \n personal union\n \n .\n \n \n [63]\n \n \n \n \n [64]\n \n \n He styled himself\n \n King of Great Britain\n \n , although this had no basis in English law.\n \n \n [65]\n \n \n Under the auspices of King James VI and I the Authorised\n \n King James Version\n \n of the Holy Bible was published in 1611. It has not only been ranked with\n \n Shakespeare\n \n \'s works as the greatest masterpiece of literature in the English language but also was the standard version of the Bible read by most Protestant Christians for four hundred years until modern revisions were produced in the 20th century.\n

\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n \n
\n The\n \n English Restoration\n \n restored the monarchy under King\n \n CharlesII\n \n and peace after the\n \n English Civil War\n \n
\n
\n
\n

\n Based on conflicting political, religious and social positions, the\n \n English Civil War\n \n was fought between the supporters of\n \n Parliament\n \n and those of King\n \n Charles I\n \n , known colloquially as\n \n Roundheads\n \n and\n \n Cavaliers\n \n respectively. This was an interwoven part of the wider multifaceted\n \n Wars of the Three Kingdoms\n \n , involving\n \n Scotland\n \n and\n \n Ireland\n \n . The Parliamentarians were victorious, Charles I was executed and the kingdom replaced by the\n \n Commonwealth\n \n . Leader of the Parliament forces,\n \n Oliver Cromwell\n \n declared himself\n \n Lord Protector\n \n in 1653; a period of\n \n personal rule\n \n followed.\n \n \n [66]\n \n \n After Cromwell\'s death and the resignation of his son\n \n Richard\n \n as Lord Protector,\n \n Charles II\n \n was invited to return as monarch in 1660, in a move called the\n \n Restoration\n \n . After the\n \n Glorious Revolution\n \n of 1688, it was constitutionally established that King and Parliament should rule together, though Parliament would have the real power. This was established with the\n \n Bill of Rights\n \n in 1689. Among the statutes set down were that the law could only be made by Parliament and could not be suspended by the King, also that the King could not impose taxes or raise an army without the prior approval of Parliament.\n \n \n [67]\n \n \n Also since that time, no British monarch has entered the\n \n House of Commons\n \n when it is sitting, which is annually commemorated at the\n \n State Opening of Parliament\n \n by the British monarch when the doors of the House of Commons are slammed in the face of the monarch\'s messenger, symbolising the rights of Parliament and its independence from the monarch.\n \n \n [68]\n \n \n \n \n [69]\n \n \n With the founding of the\n \n Royal Society\n \n in 1660, science was greatly encouraged.\n

\n

\n In 1666 the\n \n Great Fire of London\n \n gutted the City of London but it was rebuilt shortly afterwards\n \n \n [70]\n \n \n with many significant buildings designed by Sir\n \n Christopher Wren\n \n . In Parliament two factions had emerged the\n \n Tories\n \n and\n \n Whigs\n \n . Though the Tories initially supported Catholic king\n \n James II\n \n , some of them, along with the Whigs, during the\n \n Revolution of 1688\n \n invited Dutch prince William of Orange to defeat James and ultimately to become\n \n William III of England\n \n . Some English people, especially in the north, were\n \n Jacobites\n \n and continued to support James and his sons. After the parliaments of England and Scotland agreed,\n \n \n [71]\n \n \n the two countries joined in\n \n political union\n \n , to create the\n \n Kingdom of Great Britain\n \n in 1707.\n \n \n [63]\n \n \n To accommodate the union, institutions such as the law and national churches of each remained separate.\n \n \n [72]\n \n \n

\n

\n \n Late modern and contemporary\n \n

\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n \n
\n \n Saltaire\n \n , West Yorkshire, is a model mill town from the\n \n Industrial Revolution\n \n , and a\n \n World Heritage Site\n \n
\n
\n
\n

\n Under the newly formed Kingdom of Great Britain, output from the Royal Society and other\n \n English initiatives\n \n combined with the\n \n Scottish Enlightenment\n \n to create innovations in science and engineering, while the enormous growth in\n \n British overseas trade\n \n protected by the\n \n Royal Navy\n \n paved the way for the establishment of the\n \n British Empire\n \n . Domestically it drove the\n \n Industrial Revolution\n \n , a period of profound change in the\n \n socioeconomic\n \n and cultural conditions of England, resulting in industrialised agriculture, manufacture, engineering and mining, as well as new and pioneering road, rail and water networks to facilitate their expansion and development.\n \n \n [73]\n \n \n The opening of Northwest England\'s\n \n Bridgewater Canal\n \n in 1761 ushered in the\n \n canal age in Britain\n \n .\n \n \n [74]\n \n \n \n \n [75]\n \n \n In 1825 the world\'s first permanent steam locomotive-hauled passenger railway the\n \n Stockton and Darlington Railway\n \n opened to the public.\n \n \n [74]\n \n \n

\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n \n
\n \n Cotton mills\n \n in\n \n Manchester\n \n , the world\'s "first industrial city", circa 1820.\n \n \n [76]\n \n \n
\n
\n
\n

\n During the Industrial Revolution, many workers moved from England\'s countryside to new and expanding urban industrial areas to work in factories, for instance at\n \n Birmingham\n \n and\n \n Manchester\n \n , dubbed "Workshop of the World" and "Warehouse City" respectively.\n \n \n [77]\n \n \n \n \n [78]\n \n \n England maintained relative stability throughout the\n \n French Revolution\n \n ;\n \n William Pitt the Younger\n \n was British Prime Minister for the reign of\n \n George III\n \n . During the\n \n Napoleonic Wars\n \n ,\n \n Napoleon\n \n planned to\n \n invade from the south-east\n \n . However this failed to manifest and the Napoleonic forces were defeated by the British at sea by\n \n Lord Nelson\n \n and on land by the\n \n Duke of Wellington\n \n . The Napoleonic Wars fostered a concept of\n \n Britishness\n \n and a united national\n \n British people\n \n , shared with the\n \n Scots\n \n and Welsh.\n \n \n [79]\n \n \n

\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n \n
\n \n The Cenotaph, Whitehall\n \n , is a memorial to members of the\n \n British Armed Forces\n \n who died during the two World Wars\n
\n
\n
\n

\n London became the largest and most populous metropolitan area in the world during the\n \n Victorian era\n \n , and trade within the British Empire as well as the standing of the British military and navy was prestigious.\n \n \n [80]\n \n \n Political agitation at home from radicals such as the\n \n Chartists\n \n and the\n \n suffragettes\n \n enabled legislative reform and\n \n universal suffrage\n \n .\n \n \n [81]\n \n \n Power shifts in east-central Europe led to World War I; hundreds of thousands of English soldiers died fighting for the United Kingdom as part of the\n \n Allies\n \n .\n \n \n [nb 3]\n \n \n Two decades later, in\n \n World War II\n \n , the United Kingdom was again one of the\n \n Allies\n \n . At the end of the\n \n Phoney War\n \n ,\n \n Winston Churchill\n \n became the wartime Prime Minister. Developments in warfare technology saw many cities damaged by air-raids during\n \n the Blitz\n \n . Following the war, the British Empire experienced rapid\n \n decolonisation\n \n , and there was a speeding up of technological innovations; automobiles became the primary means of transport and\n \n Frank Whittle\n \n \'s development of the\n \n jet engine\n \n led to wider\n \n air travel\n \n .\n \n \n [83]\n \n \n Residential patterns were altered in England by private motoring, and by the creation of the\n \n National Health Service\n \n (NHS) in 1948. The UK\'s NHS provided\n \n publicly funded health care\n \n to all UK permanent residents free at the point of need, being paid for from general taxation. Combined, these changes prompted the reform of\n \n local government in England\n \n in the mid-20th century.\n \n \n [84]\n \n \n \n \n [85]\n \n \n

\n

\n Since the 20th century there has been significant population movement to England, mostly from other parts of the\n \n British Isles\n \n , but also from the\n \n Commonwealth\n \n , particularly the\n \n Indian subcontinent\n \n .\n \n \n [86]\n \n \n Since the 1970s there has been a large move away from manufacturing and an increasing emphasis on the\n \n service industry\n \n .\n \n \n [87]\n \n \n As part of the United Kingdom, the area joined a\n \n common market\n \n initiative called the\n \n European Economic Community\n \n which became the\n \n European Union\n \n . Since the late 20th century the\n \n administration of the United Kingdom\n \n has moved towards\n \n devolved governance\n \n in Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland.\n \n \n [88]\n \n \n \n England and Wales\n \n continues to exist as a jurisdiction within the United Kingdom.\n \n \n [89]\n \n \n Devolution has stimulated a greater emphasis on a more English-specific identity and patriotism.\n \n \n [90]\n \n \n \n \n [91]\n \n \n There is no devolved English government, but an attempt to create a similar system on a sub-regional basis was rejected by referendum.\n \n \n [92]\n \n \n

\n
\n
\n

\n \n Governance\n \n

\n

\n \n Politics\n \n

\n
\n Main article:\n \n Politics of England\n \n
\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n \n
\n The\n \n Palace of Westminster\n \n , the seat of the\n \n Parliament of the United Kingdom\n \n
\n
\n
\n

\n As part of the United Kingdom, the basic political system in England is a\n \n constitutional monarchy\n \n and\n \n parliamentary system\n \n .\n \n \n [93]\n \n \n There has not been a\n \n government of England\n \n since 1707, when the\n \n Acts of Union 1707\n \n , putting into effect the terms of the\n \n Treaty of Union\n \n , joined England and Scotland to form the\n \n Kingdom of Great Britain\n \n .\n \n \n [71]\n \n \n Before the union England was ruled by\n \n its monarch\n \n and the\n \n Parliament of England\n \n . Today England is governed directly by the\n \n Parliament of the United Kingdom\n \n , although other\n \n countries of the United Kingdom\n \n have\n \n devolved\n \n governments.\n \n \n [94]\n \n \n In the\n \n House of Commons\n \n which is the\n \n lower house\n \n of the British Parliament based at the\n \n Palace of Westminster\n \n , there are 532 Members of Parliament (MPs) for constituencies in England, out of the 650 total.\n \n \n [95]\n \n \n

\n

\n In the\n \n United Kingdom general election, 2017\n \n , the\n \n Conservative Party\n \n won 317 seats (the\n \n Speaker of the House\n \n not being counted as a Conservative), more than any other party, though not enough to achieve an overall majority. The Conservative party, headed by the prime minister\n \n Theresa May\n \n , won 55 more seats than the\n \n Labour Party\n \n , led by\n \n Jeremy Corbyn\n \n . The\n \n Scottish National Party\n \n (Scotland only) won 35 out of 59\n \n Scottish seats in the House of Commons\n \n .\n

\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n \n
\n Changing of the\n \n Queen\'s Guard\n \n at the\n \n royal residence\n \n ,\n \n Buckingham Palace\n \n
\n
\n
\n

\n As the United Kingdom is a member of the European Union, there are elections held regionally in England to decide who is sent as\n \n Members of the European Parliament\n \n . The\n \n 2014 European Parliament election\n \n saw the regions of England elect the following MEPs: 22\n \n UK Independence Party\n \n (UKIP), 17 Conservatives, 17 Labour, 3\n \n Greens\n \n , and one Liberal Democrat.\n

\n

\n Since\n \n devolution\n \n , in which other countries of the United Kingdom Scotland, Wales and\n \n Northern Ireland\n \n each have their own devolved parliament or assemblies for local issues, there has been debate about how to counterbalance this in England. Originally it was planned that various\n \n regions of England\n \n would be devolved, but following the proposal\'s rejection by the\n \n North East\n \n in a referendum, this has not been carried out.\n \n \n [92]\n \n \n

\n

\n One major issue is the\n \n West Lothian question\n \n , in which MPs from Scotland and Wales are able to vote on legislation affecting only England, while English MPs have no equivalent right to legislate on devolved matters.\n \n \n [96]\n \n \n This when placed in the context of England being the only country of the United Kingdom not to have free cancer treatment, prescriptions, residential care for the elderly and\n \n free top-up university fees\n \n ,\n \n \n [97]\n \n \n has led to a steady rise in\n \n English nationalism\n \n .\n \n \n [98]\n \n \n Some have suggested the creation of a\n \n devolved English parliament\n \n ,\n \n \n [99]\n \n \n while others have proposed simply limiting voting on legislation which only affects England to English MPs.\n \n \n [100]\n \n \n

\n
\n
\n

\n \n Law\n \n

\n
\n Main article:\n \n English law\n \n
\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n \n
\n The\n \n Royal Courts of Justice\n \n
\n
\n
\n

\n The\n \n English law\n \n legal system, developed over the centuries, is the basis of\n \n common law\n \n \n \n [101]\n \n \n legal systems used in most\n \n Commonwealth\n \n countries\n \n \n [102]\n \n \n and the United States (except\n \n Louisiana\n \n ). Despite now being part of the United Kingdom, the legal system of the\n \n Courts of England and Wales\n \n continued, under the\n \n Treaty of Union\n \n , as a separate legal system from the one used in Scotland. The general essence of English law is that it is made by judges sitting in courts, applying their common sense and knowledge of\n \n legal precedent\n \n \n \n \n stare decisis\n \n \n to the facts before them.\n \n \n [103]\n \n \n

\n

\n The\n \n court system\n \n is headed by the Senior Courts of England and Wales, consisting of the\n \n Court of Appeal\n \n , the\n \n High Court of Justice\n \n for civil cases, and the\n \n Crown Court\n \n for criminal cases.\n \n \n [104]\n \n \n The\n \n Supreme Court of the United Kingdom\n \n is the highest court for criminal and civil cases in\n \n England and Wales\n \n . It was created in 2009 after constitutional changes, taking over the\n \n judicial functions of the House of Lords\n \n .\n \n \n [105]\n \n \n A decision of the Supreme Court is binding on every other court in the hierarchy, which must follow its directions.\n \n \n [106]\n \n \n

\n

\n Crime increased between 1981 and 1995 but fell by 42% in the period 19952006.\n \n \n [107]\n \n \n The prison population doubled over the same period, giving it the\n \n highest incarceration rate\n \n in Western Europe at 147 per 100,000.\n \n \n [108]\n \n \n \n Her Majesty\'s Prison Service\n \n , reporting to the\n \n Ministry of Justice\n \n , manages most\n \n prisons\n \n , housing over 85,000 convicts.\n \n \n [109]\n \n \n

\n

\n
\n \n South\n
\n Yorks.\n \n

\n
\n \n Ceremonial counties of England\n \n
\n
\n
\n

\n The\n \n subdivisions of England\n \n consist of up to four levels of\n \n subnational division\n \n controlled through a variety of types of administrative entities created for the purposes of\n \n local government\n \n . The highest tier of local government were the nine\n \n regions of England\n \n :\n \n North East\n \n ,\n \n North West\n \n ,\n \n Yorkshire and the Humber\n \n ,\n \n East Midlands\n \n ,\n \n West Midlands\n \n ,\n \n East\n \n ,\n \n South East\n \n ,\n \n South West\n \n , and London. These were created in 1994 as\n \n Government Offices\n \n , used by the UK government to deliver a wide range of policies and programmes regionally, but there are no elected bodies at this level, except in London, and in 2011 the regional government offices were abolished.\n \n \n [110]\n \n \n The same boundaries remain in use for electing\n \n Members of the European Parliament\n \n on a regional basis.\n

\n

\n After\n \n devolution\n \n began to take place in other parts of the United Kingdom it was planned that referendums for the regions of England would take place for their own elected\n \n regional assemblies\n \n as a counterweight.\n \n London accepted\n \n in 1998: the\n \n London Assembly\n \n was created two years later. However, when the proposal was rejected by the\n \n northern England devolution referendums, 2004\n \n in the North East, further referendums were cancelled.\n \n \n [92]\n \n \n The regional assemblies outside London were abolished in 2010, and their functions transferred to respective\n \n Regional Development Agencies\n \n and a new system of\n \n Local authority leaders\' boards\n \n .\n \n \n [111]\n \n \n

\n

\n Below the regional level, all of England is divided into 48\n \n ceremonial counties\n \n .\n \n \n [112]\n \n \n These are used primarily as a geographical frame of reference and have developed gradually since the\n \n Middle Ages\n \n , with some established as recently as 1974.\n \n \n [113]\n \n \n Each has a\n \n Lord Lieutenant\n \n and\n \n High Sheriff\n \n ; these posts are used to represent the\n \n British monarch\n \n locally.\n \n \n [112]\n \n \n Outside\n \n Greater London\n \n and the\n \n Isles of Scilly\n \n , England is also divided into 83\n \n metropolitan and non-metropolitan counties\n \n ; these correspond to areas used for the purposes of local government\n \n \n [114]\n \n \n and may consist of a single district or be divided into several.\n

\n

\n There are six\n \n metropolitan counties\n \n based on the most heavily urbanised areas, which do not have county councils.\n \n \n [114]\n \n \n In these areas the principal authorities are the councils of the subdivisions, the\n \n metropolitan boroughs\n \n . Elsewhere, 27\n \n non-metropolitan "shire" counties\n \n have a\n \n county council\n \n and are divided into districts, each with a district council. They are typically, though not always, found in more rural areas. The remaining non-metropolitan counties are of a single district and usually correspond to large towns or sparsely populated counties; they are known as\n \n unitary authorities\n \n . Greater London has a different system for local government, with 32\n \n London boroughs\n \n , plus the\n \n City of London\n \n covering a small area at the core governed by the\n \n City of London Corporation\n \n .\n \n \n [115]\n \n \n At the most localised level, much of England is divided into\n \n civil parishes\n \n with\n \n councils\n \n ; in Greater London only one,\n \n Queen\'s Park\n \n , exists as of 2014\n \n \n [update]\n \n \n after they were\n \n abolished in 1965\n \n until legislation\n \n allowed their recreation\n \n in 2007.\n

\n

\n \n Geography\n \n

\n
\n Main article:\n \n Geography of England\n \n
\n

\n \n Landscape and rivers\n \n

\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n \n
\n \n Skiddaw\n \n massif, seen from\n \n Walla Crag\n \n in the\n \n Lake District\n \n
\n
\n
\n

\n Geographically England includes the central and southern two-thirds of the island of Great Britain, plus such offshore islands as the\n \n Isle of Wight\n \n and the\n \n Isles of Scilly\n \n . It is bordered by two other countries of the United Kingdom:\n \n to the north\n \n by Scotland and\n \n to the west\n \n by Wales. England is closer to the European continent than any other part of mainland Britain. It is separated from\n \n France\n \n (\n \n Hauts-de-France\n \n ) by a 21-mile (34km)\n \n \n [116]\n \n \n sea gap, though the two countries are connected by the\n \n Channel Tunnel\n \n near\n \n Folkestone\n \n .\n \n \n [117]\n \n \n England also has shores on the\n \n Irish Sea\n \n ,\n \n North Sea\n \n and Atlantic Ocean.\n

\n

\n The ports of London,\n \n Liverpool\n \n , and\n \n Newcastle\n \n lie on the tidal rivers\n \n Thames\n \n ,\n \n Mersey\n \n and\n \n Tyne\n \n respectively. At 220 miles (350km), the\n \n Severn\n \n is the longest river flowing through England.\n \n \n [118]\n \n \n It empties into the\n \n Bristol Channel\n \n and is notable for its\n \n Severn Bore\n \n (a\n \n tidal bore\n \n ), which can reach 2 metres (6.6ft) in height.\n \n \n [119]\n \n \n However, the longest river entirely in England is the Thames, which is 215 miles (346km) in length.\n \n \n [120]\n \n \n There are many\n \n lakes in England\n \n ; the largest is\n \n Windermere\n \n , within the aptly named\n \n Lake District\n \n .\n \n \n [121]\n \n \n

\n

\n Most of England\'s landscape consists of low hills and plains, with upland and mountainous terrain in the north and west of the country. The northern uplands include the\n \n Pennines\n \n , a chain of uplands dividing east and west, the Lake District mountains in Cumbria, and the\n \n Cheviot Hills\n \n , straddling the border between England and Scotland. The highest point in England, at 978 metres (3,209ft), is\n \n Scafell Pike\n \n in the Lake District.\n \n \n [121]\n \n \n The\n \n Shropshire Hills\n \n are near Wales while\n \n Dartmoor\n \n and\n \n Exmoor\n \n are two upland areas in the south-west of the country. The approximate dividing line between terrain types is often indicated by the\n \n Tees-Exe line\n \n .\n \n \n [122]\n \n \n

\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n \n
\n Terrain of\n \n Dartmoor\n \n , Devon\n
\n
\n
\n

\n In geological terms, the Pennines, known as the "backbone of England", are the oldest range of mountains in the country, originating from the end of the\n \n Paleozoic Era\n \n around 300million years ago.\n \n \n [123]\n \n \n Their geological composition includes, among others,\n \n sandstone\n \n and\n \n limestone\n \n , and also coal. There are\n \n karst\n \n landscapes in calcite areas such as parts of\n \n Yorkshire\n \n and\n \n Derbyshire\n \n . The Pennine landscape is high\n \n moorland\n \n in upland areas, indented by fertile valleys of the region\'s rivers. They contain two\n \n national parks\n \n , the\n \n Yorkshire Dales\n \n and the\n \n Peak District\n \n . In the\n \n West Country\n \n , Dartmoor and Exmoor of the Southwest Peninsula include upland moorland supported by granite, and enjoy a\n \n mild climate\n \n ; both are national parks.\n \n \n [124]\n \n \n

\n

\n The\n \n English Lowlands\n \n are in the central and southern regions of the country, consisting of green rolling hills, including the\n \n Cotswold Hills\n \n ,\n \n Chiltern Hills\n \n ,\n \n North\n \n and\n \n South Downs\n \n ; where they meet the sea they form white rock exposures such as the\n \n cliffs of Dover\n \n . This also includes relatively flat plains such as the\n \n Salisbury Plain\n \n ,\n \n Somerset Levels\n \n ,\n \n South Coast Plain\n \n and\n \n The Fens\n \n .\n

\n
\n
\n

\n \n Climate\n \n

\n
\n Main article:\n \n Climate of England\n \n
\n

\n England has a\n \n temperate\n \n \n maritime climate\n \n : it is mild with temperatures not much lower than 0C (32F) in winter and not much higher than 32C (90F) in summer.\n \n \n [125]\n \n \n The weather is damp relatively frequently and is changeable. The coldest months are January and February, the latter particularly on the\n \n English coast\n \n , while July is normally the warmest month. Months with mild to warm weather are May, June, September and October.\n \n \n [125]\n \n \n Rainfall is spread fairly evenly throughout the year.\n

\n

\n Important influences on the climate of England are its proximity to the\n \n Atlantic Ocean\n \n , its northern\n \n latitude\n \n and the warming of the sea by the\n \n Gulf Stream\n \n .\n \n \n [125]\n \n \n Rainfall is higher in the west, and parts of the\n \n Lake District\n \n receive more rain than anywhere else in the country.\n \n \n [125]\n \n \n Since weather records began, the highest temperature recorded was 38.5C (101.3F) on 10 August 2003 at\n \n Brogdale\n \n in Kent,\n \n \n [126]\n \n \n while the lowest was 26.1C (15.0F) on 10 January 1982 in\n \n Edgmond\n \n , Shropshire.\n \n \n [127]\n \n \n

\n

\n \n Major conurbations\n \n

\n
\n See also:\n \n List of places in England\n \n
\n

\n The\n \n Greater London Built-up Area\n \n is by far the largest urban area in England\n \n \n [128]\n \n \n and one of the busiest cities in the world. It is considered a\n \n global city\n \n and has a population larger than other countries in the United Kingdom besides England itself.\n \n \n [128]\n \n \n Other urban areas of considerable size and influence tend to be in\n \n northern England\n \n or the\n \n English Midlands\n \n .\n \n \n [128]\n \n \n There are\n \n 50 settlements\n \n which have been designated\n \n city status in England\n \n , while the wider United Kingdom has 66.\n

\n

\n While many cities in England are quite large, such as\n \n Birmingham\n \n ,\n \n Sheffield\n \n , Manchester,\n \n Liverpool\n \n ,\n \n Leeds\n \n ,\n \n Newcastle\n \n ,\n \n Bradford\n \n ,\n \n Nottingham\n \n , population size is not a prerequisite for city status.\n \n \n [129]\n \n \n Traditionally the status was given to towns with\n \n diocesan cathedrals\n \n , so there are smaller cities like\n \n Wells\n \n ,\n \n Ely\n \n ,\n \n Ripon\n \n ,\n \n Truro\n \n and\n \n Chichester\n \n .\n

\n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n
