\n \n Economy\n \n

\n
\n Main article:\n \n Economy of England\n \n
\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n \n
\n The\n \n City of London\n \n is the financial capital of the United Kingdom\n \n \n [130]\n \n \n \n \n [131]\n \n \n
\n
\n
\n

\n England\'s economy is one of the largest in the world, with an average\n \n GDP per capita\n \n of 22,907.\n \n \n [132]\n \n \n Usually regarded as a\n \n mixed market economy\n \n , it has adopted many\n \n free market\n \n principles, yet maintains an advanced social welfare infrastructure.\n \n \n [133]\n \n \n The official currency in England is the\n \n pound sterling\n \n , whose\n \n ISO 4217\n \n code is GBP.\n \n Taxation in England\n \n is quite competitive when\n \n compared\n \n to much of the rest of Europe as of 2014\n \n \n [update]\n \n \n the basic rate of personal tax is 20% on taxable income up to 31,865 above the personal tax-free allowance (normally 10,000), and 40% on any additional earnings above that amount.\n \n \n [134]\n \n \n

\n

\n The economy of England is the largest part of the\n \n UK\'s economy\n \n ,\n \n \n [132]\n \n \n which has the\n \n 18th\n \n highest GDP\n \n PPP\n \n per capita in the world. England is a leader in the chemical\n \n \n [135]\n \n \n and pharmaceutical sectors and in key technical industries, particularly\n \n aerospace\n \n , the\n \n arms industry\n \n , and the manufacturing side of the\n \n software industry\n \n . London, home to the\n \n London Stock Exchange\n \n , the United Kingdom\'s main\n \n stock exchange\n \n and the largest in Europe, is England\'s financial centre, with 100 of Europe\'s 500largest corporations being based there.\n \n \n [136]\n \n \n London is the largest financial centre in Europe, and as of 2014\n \n \n [update]\n \n \n is the second largest in the world.\n \n \n [137]\n \n \n

\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n \n
\n The\n \n Bentley Mulsanne\n \n .\n \n Bentley\n \n is a well-known English car company\n
\n
\n
\n

\n The\n \n Bank of England\n \n , founded in 1694 by Scottish banker\n \n William Paterson\n \n , is the United Kingdom\'s\n \n central bank\n \n . Originally established as private banker to the government of England, since 1946 it has been a\n \n state-owned institution\n \n .\n \n \n [138]\n \n \n The bank has a monopoly on the issue of banknotes in\n \n England and Wales\n \n , although not in other parts of the United Kingdom. The government has devolved responsibility to the bank\'s\n \n Monetary Policy Committee\n \n for managing the monetary policy of the country and setting interest rates.\n \n \n [139]\n \n \n

\n

\n England is highly industrialised, but since the 1970s there has been a decline in traditional heavy and manufacturing industries, and an increasing emphasis on a more\n \n service industry\n \n oriented economy.\n \n \n [87]\n \n \n Tourism has become a significant industry, attracting millions of visitors to England each year. The export part of the economy is dominated by\n \n pharmaceuticals\n \n , cars (although many English\n \n marques\n \n are now foreign-owned, such as\n \n Land Rover\n \n ,\n \n Lotus\n \n ,\n \n Jaguar\n \n and\n \n Bentley\n \n ),\n \n crude oil\n \n and petroleum from the English parts of\n \n North Sea oil\n \n along with\n \n Wytch Farm\n \n ,\n \n aircraft engines\n \n and alcoholic beverages.\n \n \n [140]\n \n \n

\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n \n
\n \n Clarks\n \n was founded in 1825 and has since become a popular shoe brand internationally, seen as specialists in school shoes for children\n
\n
\n
\n

\n Most of the UK\'s 30 billion\n \n \n [141]\n \n \n \n aerospace industry\n \n is primarily based in England. The global market opportunity for UK aerospace manufacturers over the next two decades is estimated at 3.5 trillion.\n \n \n [142]\n \n \n \n GKN Aerospace\n \n an expert in metallic and composite aerostructures is involved in almost every civil and military fixed and rotary wing aircraft in production is based in\n \n Redditch\n \n .\n \n \n [143]\n \n \n

\n

\n \n BAE Systems\n \n makes large sections of the\n \n Typhoon Eurofighter\n \n at its sub-assembly plant in\n \n Salmesbury\n \n and assembles the aircraft for the RAF at its\n \n Warton\n \n plant, near\n \n Preston\n \n . It is also a principal subcontractor on the\n \n F35 Joint Strike Fighter\n \n the world\'s largest single defence project for which it designs and manufactures a range of components including the aft fuselage, vertical and horizontal tail and wing tips and fuel system. It also manufactures the\n \n Hawk\n \n , the world\'s most successful jet training aircraft.\n \n \n [143]\n \n \n

\n

\n \n Rolls-Royce PLC\n \n is the world\'s second-largest\n \n aero-engine\n \n manufacturer. Its engines power more than 30 types of commercial aircraft, and it has more 30,000 engines currently in service across both the civil and defence sectors. With a workforce of over 12,000 people,\n \n Derby\n \n has the largest concentration of Rolls-Royce employees in the UK. Rolls-Royce also produces low-emission power systems for ships; makes critical equipment and safety systems for the nuclear industry and powers offshore platforms and major pipelines for the oil and gas industry.\n \n \n [143]\n \n \n \n \n [144]\n \n \n

\n

\n Much of the UK\'s space industry is centred on\n \n EADS Astrium\n \n , based in\n \n Stevenage\n \n and\n \n Portsmouth\n \n . The company builds the\n \n buses\n \n the underlying structure onto which the payload and propulsion systems are built for most of the\n \n European Space Agency\n \n \'s spacecraft, as well as commercial\n \n satellites\n \n . The world leader in compact satellite systems,\n \n Surrey Satellites\n \n , is also part of Astrium.\n \n \n [143]\n \n \n \n Reaction Engines Limited\n \n , the company planning to build\n \n Skylon\n \n , a single-stage-to-orbit spaceplane using their\n \n SABRE rocket engine\n \n , a combined-cycle, air-breathing rocket propulsion system is based\n \n Culham\n \n .\n

\n

\n Agriculture is intensive and highly mechanised, producing 60% of food needs with only 2% of the labour force.\n \n \n [145]\n \n \n Two-thirds of production is devoted to livestock, the other to arable crops.\n \n \n [146]\n \n \n

\n

\n \n Science and technology\n \n

\n
\n Main articles:\n \n List of English inventions and discoveries\n \n and\n \n Royal Society\n \n
\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n \n
\n Sir\n \n Isaac Newton\n \n is one of the most influential figures in the\n \n history of science\n \n
\n
\n
\n

\n Prominent English figures from the field of science and mathematics include Sir\n \n Isaac Newton\n \n ,\n \n Michael Faraday\n \n ,\n \n Charles Darwin\n \n ,\n \n Robert Hooke\n \n ,\n \n James Prescott Joule\n \n ,\n \n John Dalton\n \n ,\n \n Lord Rayleigh\n \n ,\n \n J. J. Thomson\n \n ,\n \n James Chadwick\n \n ,\n \n Charles Babbage\n \n ,\n \n George Boole\n \n ,\n \n Alan Turing\n \n ,\n \n Tim Berners-Lee\n \n ,\n \n Paul Dirac\n \n ,\n \n Stephen Hawking\n \n ,\n \n Peter Higgs\n \n ,\n \n Roger Penrose\n \n ,\n \n John Horton Conway\n \n ,\n \n Thomas Bayes\n \n ,\n \n Arthur Cayley\n \n ,\n \n G. H. Hardy\n \n ,\n \n Oliver Heaviside\n \n ,\n \n Andrew Wiles\n \n ,\n \n Francis Crick\n \n ,\n \n Joseph Lister\n \n ,\n \n Joseph Priestley\n \n ,\n \n Thomas Young\n \n ,\n \n Christopher Wren\n \n and\n \n Richard Dawkins\n \n . Some experts claim that the earliest concept of a\n \n metric system\n \n was invented by\n \n John Wilkins\n \n , the first secretary of the\n \n Royal Society\n \n , in 1668.\n \n \n [147]\n \n \n

\n

\n As the birthplace of the\n \n Industrial Revolution\n \n , England was home to many significant inventors during the late 18th and early 19th centuries. Famous English engineers include\n \n Isambard Kingdom Brunel\n \n , best known for the creation of the\n \n Great Western Railway\n \n , a series of famous\n \n steamships\n \n , and numerous important bridges, hence revolutionising public transport and modern-day engineering.\n \n \n [148]\n \n \n \n Thomas Newcomen\n \n \'s\n \n steam engine\n \n helped spawn the Industrial Revolution.\n \n \n [149]\n \n \n The Father of Railways,\n \n George Stephenson\n \n , built the first public inter-city railway line in the world, the\n \n Liverpool and Manchester Railway\n \n , which opened in 1830. With his role in the marketing and manufacturing of the steam engine, and invention of modern coinage,\n \n Matthew Boulton\n \n (business partner of\n \n James Watt\n \n ) is regarded as one of the most influential entrepreneurs in history.\n \n \n [150]\n \n \n The physician\n \n Edward Jenner\n \n \'s\n \n smallpox vaccine\n \n is said to have "saved more lives... than were lost in all the wars of mankind since the beginning of recorded history."\n \n \n [151]\n \n \n \n \n [152]\n \n \n \n \n [153]\n \n \n

\n

\n Inventions and discoveries of the English include: the\n \n jet engine\n \n , the first industrial\n \n spinning machine\n \n ,\n \n the first computer\n \n and the first\n \n modern computer\n \n , the\n \n World Wide Web\n \n along with\n \n HTML\n \n , the first successful human\n \n blood transfusion\n \n , the motorised\n \n vacuum cleaner\n \n ,\n \n \n [154]\n \n \n the\n \n lawn mower\n \n , the\n \n seat belt\n \n , the\n \n hovercraft\n \n , the\n \n electric motor\n \n ,\n \n steam engines\n \n , and theories such as the Darwinian theory of\n \n evolution\n \n and\n \n atomic theory\n \n . Newton developed the ideas of\n \n universal gravitation\n \n ,\n \n Newtonian mechanics\n \n , and\n \n calculus\n \n , and\n \n Robert Hooke\n \n his eponymously named\n \n law of elasticity\n \n . Other inventions include the iron plate railway, the\n \n thermosiphon\n \n ,\n \n tarmac\n \n , the\n \n rubber band\n \n , the\n \n mousetrap\n \n ,\n \n "cat\'s eye"\n \n \n road marker\n \n , joint development of the\n \n light bulb\n \n , steam\n \n locomotives\n \n , the modern\n \n seed drill\n \n and many modern techniques and technologies used in\n \n precision engineering\n \n .\n \n \n [155]\n \n \n

\n
\n
\n

\n \n Transport\n \n

\n
\n Main article:\n \n Transport in England\n \n
\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n \n
\n \n Heathrow Airport\n \n has more international\n \n passenger traffic\n \n than any other airport in the world.\n \n \n [156]\n \n \n
\n
\n
\n

\n The\n \n Department for Transport\n \n is the government body responsible for overseeing transport in England. There are many\n \n motorways in England\n \n , and many other trunk roads, such as the\n \n A1 Great North Road\n \n , which runs through eastern England from London to Newcastle\n \n \n [157]\n \n \n (much of this section is motorway) and onward to the Scottish border. The longest motorway in England is the\n \n M6\n \n , from\n \n Rugby\n \n through the\n \n North West\n \n up to the\n \n Anglo-Scottish border\n \n , a distance of 232 miles (373km).\n \n \n [157]\n \n \n Other major routes include: the\n \n M1\n \n from London to Leeds, the\n \n M25\n \n which encircles London, the\n \n M60\n \n which encircles Manchester, the\n \n M4\n \n from London to South Wales, the\n \n M62\n \n from Liverpool via Manchester to East Yorkshire, and the\n \n M5\n \n from Birmingham to Bristol and the South West.\n \n \n [157]\n \n \n

\n

\n Bus transport across the country is widespread; major companies include\n \n National Express\n \n ,\n \n Arriva\n \n and\n \n Go-Ahead Group\n \n . The red\n \n double-decker buses\n \n in London have become a symbol of England. There is a\n \n rapid transit\n \n network in two English cities: the\n \n London Underground\n \n ; and the\n \n Tyne and Wear Metro\n \n in Newcastle, Gateshead and Sunderland.\n \n \n [158]\n \n \n There are several tram networks, such as the\n \n Blackpool tramway\n \n ,\n \n Manchester Metrolink\n \n ,\n \n Sheffield Supertram\n \n and\n \n Midland Metro\n \n , and the\n \n Tramlink\n \n system centred on Croydon in South London.\n \n \n [158]\n \n \n

\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n \n
\n The\n \n Metropolitan Railway\n \n , now part of the\n \n London Underground\n \n was the first underground railway in the world\n
\n
\n
\n

\n \n Rail transport in England\n \n is the oldest in the world: passenger railways originated in England in 1825.\n \n \n [159]\n \n \n Much of Britain\'s 10,000 miles (16,000km) of rail network lies in England, covering the country fairly extensively, although a high proportion of railway lines were closed in the second half of the 20th century. There are plans to reopen lines such as the\n \n Varsity Line\n \n between Oxford and Cambridge. These lines are mostly standard gauge (\n \n single\n \n ,\n \n double\n \n or\n \n quadruple track\n \n ) though there are also a few\n \n narrow gauge lines\n \n . There is rail transport access to France and Belgium through an undersea rail link, the\n \n Channel Tunnel\n \n , which was completed in 1994.\n

\n

\n England has extensive domestic and international aviation links. The largest airport is\n \n Heathrow\n \n , which is the\n \n world\'s busiest airport measured by number of international passengers\n \n .\n \n \n [160]\n \n \n Other large airports include\n \n Manchester Airport\n \n ,\n \n Stansted Airport\n \n ,\n \n Luton Airport\n \n and\n \n Birmingham Airport\n \n .\n \n \n [156]\n \n \n By sea there is ferry transport, both local and international, including to Ireland, the Netherlands and Belgium.\n \n \n [161]\n \n \n There are around 4,400 miles (7,100km) of navigable waterways in England, half of which is owned by the\n \n Canal and River Trust\n \n ,\n \n \n [161]\n \n \n however, water transport is very limited. The\n \n Thames\n \n is the major waterway in England, with imports and exports focused at the\n \n Port of Tilbury\n \n in the Thames Estuary, one of the United Kingdom\'s three major ports.\n \n \n [161]\n \n \n

\n

\n \n Healthcare\n \n

\n
\n Main article:\n \n Healthcare in England\n \n
\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n \n
\n The\n \n Queen Elizabeth Hospital\n \n in\n \n Birmingham\n \n has the largest single floor critical care unit in the world\n
\n
\n
\n

\n The\n \n National Health Service\n \n (NHS) is the\n \n publicly funded healthcare system\n \n in England responsible for providing the majority of healthcare in the country. The NHS began on 5 July 1948, putting into effect the provisions of the\n \n National Health Service Act 1946\n \n . It was based on the findings of the\n \n Beveridge Report\n \n , prepared by economist and social reformer\n \n William Beveridge\n \n .\n \n \n [162]\n \n \n The NHS is largely funded from general taxation including\n \n National Insurance\n \n payments,\n \n \n [163]\n \n \n and it provides most of its services free at the point of use, although there are charges for some people for eye tests, dental care, prescriptions and aspects of personal care.\n \n \n [164]\n \n \n

\n

\n The government department responsible for the NHS is the\n \n Department of Health\n \n , headed by the\n \n Secretary of State for Health\n \n , who sits in the\n \n British Cabinet\n \n . Most of the expenditure of the Department of Health is spent on the NHS98.6billion was spent in 20082009.\n \n \n [165]\n \n \n In recent years the private sector has been increasingly used to provide more NHS services despite opposition by doctors and trade unions.\n \n \n [166]\n \n \n

\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n \n
\n Life expectancy at birth in England and Wales 2012 to 2014. Lighter colours indicate longer life expectancy.\n
\n
\n
\n

\n The average\n \n life expectancy\n \n of people in England is 77.5 years for males and 81.7 years for females, the highest of the four\n \n countries of the United Kingdom\n \n .\n \n \n [167]\n \n \n The South of England has a higher life expectancy than the North, however, regional differences do seem to be slowly narrowing: between 19911993 and 20122014, life expectancy in the North East increased by 6.0 years and in the North West by 5.8 years, the fastest increase in any region outside London, and the gap between life expectancy in the North East and South East is now 2.5 years, down from 2.9 in 1993.\n \n \n [167]\n \n \n

\n

\n \n Demography\n \n

\n
\n Main article:\n \n Demography of England\n \n
\n

\n \n Population\n \n

\n
\n Main article:\n \n English people\n \n
\n
\n See also:\n \n English diaspora\n \n ,\n \n Cornish people\n \n , and\n \n List of urban areas in the United Kingdom\n \n
\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n \n
\n The\n \n metropolitan\n \n and\n \n non-metropolitan counties\n \n , colour-coded to show population\n
\n
\n
\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n \n
\n Population of England and Wales by administrative areas. Their size shows their population, with some approximation. Each group of squares in the map key is 20% of total number of districts.\n
\n
\n
\n

\n With over 53million inhabitants, England is by far the most populous country of the United Kingdom, accounting for 84% of the combined total.\n \n \n [11]\n \n \n \n \n [168]\n \n \n England taken as a unit and measured against international states has the fourth largest population in the European Union and would be the 25th largest\n \n country by population\n \n in the world.\n \n \n [169]\n \n \n With a density of 424 people per square kilometre, it would be the second most densely populated country in the European Union after\n \n Malta\n \n .\n \n \n [170]\n \n \n \n \n [171]\n \n \n

\n

\n The\n \n English people\n \n are a\n \n British people\n \n .\n \n \n [172]\n \n \n Some genetic evidence suggests that 7595% descend in the paternal line from prehistoric settlers who originally came from the\n \n Iberian Peninsula\n \n , as well as a 5% contribution from\n \n Angles\n \n and\n \n Saxons\n \n , and a significant Scandinavian (\n \n Viking\n \n ) element.\n \n \n [173]\n \n \n \n \n [174]\n \n \n \n \n [175]\n \n \n However, other geneticists place the\n \n Germanic\n \n estimate up to half.\n \n \n [176]\n \n \n \n \n [177]\n \n \n Over time, various cultures have been influential:\n \n Prehistoric\n \n ,\n \n Brythonic\n \n ,\n \n \n [178]\n \n \n \n Roman\n \n ,\n \n Anglo-Saxon\n \n ,\n \n \n [179]\n \n \n \n Viking\n \n (North Germanic),\n \n \n [180]\n \n \n \n Gaelic\n \n cultures, as well as a large influence from\n \n Normans\n \n . There is an English diaspora in former parts of the British Empire; especially the United States, Canada, Australia, South Africa and New Zealand.\n \n \n [nb 4]\n \n \n Since the late 1990s, many English people\n \n have migrated\n \n to Spain.\n \n \n [185]\n \n \n \n \n [186]\n \n \n

\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n \n
\n 2009 estimates of\n \n ethnic groups in England\n \n \n \n [187]\n \n \n
\n
\n
\n

\n In 1086, when the\n \n \n Domesday Book\n \n \n was compiled, England had a population of two million. About 10% lived in urban areas.\n \n \n [188]\n \n \n By 1801, the population was 8.3million, and by 1901 30.5million.\n \n \n [189]\n \n \n Due in particular to the economic prosperity of\n \n South East England\n \n , it has received many economic migrants from the other parts of the United Kingdom.\n \n \n [172]\n \n \n There has been\n \n significant Irish migration\n \n .\n \n \n [190]\n \n \n The proportion of ethnically European residents totals at 87.50%, including\n \n Germans\n \n \n \n [191]\n \n \n and\n \n Poles\n \n .\n \n \n [172]\n \n \n

\n

\n Other people from much further afield in the former British colonies have arrived since the 1950s: in particular, 6% of people living in England have family origins in the\n \n Indian subcontinent\n \n , mostly\n \n India\n \n ,\n \n Pakistan\n \n and\n \n Bangladesh\n \n .\n \n \n [172]\n \n \n \n \n [191]\n \n \n 2.90% of the population are black, from Africa and the\n \n Caribbean\n \n , especially former British colonies.\n \n \n [172]\n \n \n \n \n [191]\n \n \n There is a significant number of Chinese and\n \n British Chinese\n \n .\n \n \n [172]\n \n \n \n \n [191]\n \n \n In 2007, 22% of primary school children in England were from\n \n ethnic minority\n \n families,\n \n \n [192]\n \n \n and in 2011 that figure was 26.5%.\n \n \n [193]\n \n \n About half of the population increase between 1991 and 2001 was due to immigration.\n \n \n [194]\n \n \n Debate over immigration is politically prominent;\n \n \n [195]\n \n \n 80% of respondents in a 2009\n \n Home Office\n \n poll wanted to cap it.\n \n \n [196]\n \n \n The\n \n ONS\n \n has projected that the population will grow by nine million between 2014 and 2039.\n \n \n [197]\n \n \n

\n

\n England contains one indigenous national minority, the\n \n Cornish people\n \n , recognised by the UK government under the\n \n Framework Convention for the Protection of National Minorities\n \n in 2014.\n \n \n [198]\n \n \n

\n

\n \n Language\n \n

\n
\n Further information:\n \n English language in England\n \n
\n
\n See also:\n \n English language\n \n ,\n \n History of the English language\n \n , and\n \n Cornish language\n \n
\n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n
\n Language\n \n Native speakers\n \n \n [199]\n \n \n
\n English\n \n 46,936,780\n
\n \n Polish\n \n \n 529,173\n
\n \n Punjabi\n \n \n 271,580\n
\n \n Urdu\n \n \n 266,330\n
\n \n Bengali\n \n \n 216,196\n
\n \n Gujarati\n \n \n 212,217\n
\n \n Arabic\n \n \n 152,490\n
\n French\n \n 145,026\n
\n \n Portuguese\n \n \n 131,002\n
\n \n Welsh\n \n \n 8,248\n
\n \n Cornish\n \n \n 554\n
\n Other\n \n 2,267,016\n
\n Population\n \n \n 51,005,610\n \n
\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n \n
\n \n English-speaking world\n \n
\n \n \n Majority native language\n
\n
\n \n \n Official, but not majority language\n
\n \n Note: English is also an\n \n official language of the EU\n \n \n \n \n [200]\n \n \n
\n
\n
\n

\n As its name suggests, the English language, today spoken by hundreds of millions of people around the world, originated as the language of England, where it remains the principal tongue spoken by 98% of the population.\n \n \n [201]\n \n \n It is an\n \n Indo-European\n \n language in the\n \n Anglo-Frisian\n \n branch of the\n \n Germanic\n \n family.\n \n \n [202]\n \n \n After the\n \n Norman conquest\n \n , the\n \n Old English\n \n language was displaced and confined to the\n \n lower social classes\n \n as\n \n Norman French\n \n and\n \n Latin\n \n were used by the aristocracy.\n

\n

\n By the 15th century, English was back in fashion among all classes, though much changed; the\n \n Middle English\n \n form showed many signs of French influence, both in vocabulary and spelling. During the\n \n English Renaissance\n \n , many words were coined from Latin and Greek origins.\n \n \n [203]\n \n \n \n Modern English\n \n has extended this custom of flexibility when it comes to incorporating words from different languages. Thanks in large part to the\n \n British Empire\n \n , the English language is the world\'s unofficial\n \n \n lingua franca\n \n \n .\n \n \n [204]\n \n \n

\n

\n \n English language learning and teaching\n \n is an important\n \n economic activity\n \n , and includes\n \n language schooling\n \n , tourism spending, and publishing. There is no\n \n legislation\n \n mandating an\n \n official language\n \n for England,\n \n \n [205]\n \n \n but English is the only language used for official business. Despite the country\'s relatively small size, there are many distinct\n \n regional accents\n \n , and individuals with particularly strong accents may not be easily understood everywhere in the country.\n

\n

\n As well as English, England has two other\n \n indigenous languages\n \n ,\n \n Cornish\n \n and\n \n Welsh\n \n . Cornish died out as a community language in the 18th century but is being revived,\n \n \n [206]\n \n \n \n \n [207]\n \n \n and is now protected under the\n \n European Charter for Regional or Minority Languages\n \n .\n \n \n [208]\n \n \n It is spoken by 0.1% of people in\n \n Cornwall\n \n ,\n \n \n [209]\n \n \n and is taught to some degree in several primary and secondary schools.\n \n \n [210]\n \n \n \n \n [211]\n \n \n

\n

\n When the modern border between Wales and England was established by the\n \n Laws in Wales Acts 1535 and 1542\n \n , many Welsh-speaking communities found themselves on the English side of the border. Welsh was spoken in\n \n Archenfield\n \n in Herefordshire into the nineteenth century,\n \n \n [212]\n \n \n and by natives of parts of western\n \n Shropshire\n \n until the middle of the twentieth century if not later.\n \n \n [213]\n \n \n

\n

\n \n State schools\n \n teach students a\n \n second language\n \n , usually French, German or Spanish.\n \n \n [214]\n \n \n Due to immigration, it was reported in 2007 that around 800,000 school students spoke a\n \n foreign language\n \n at home,\n \n \n [192]\n \n \n the most common being\n \n Punjabi\n \n and\n \n Urdu\n \n . However, following the 2011 census data released by the\n \n Office for National Statistics\n \n , figures now show that Polish is the main language spoken in England after English.\n \n \n [215]\n \n \n

\n

\n \n Religion\n \n

\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n \n
\n \n Canterbury Cathedral\n \n , seat of the\n \n Archbishop of Canterbury\n \n
\n
\n
\n
\n Main article:\n \n Religion in England\n \n
\n
\n Further information:\n \n History of Christianity in England\n \n
\n

\n In the 2011 census, 59.4% of the population of England specified their religion as Christian, 24.7% answered that they had no religion, 5% specified that they were\n \n Muslim\n \n , while 3.7% of the population belongs to other religions and 7.2% did not give an answer.\n \n \n [216]\n \n \n Christianity is the most widely practised religion in England, as it has been since the Early Middle Ages, although it was first introduced much earlier in Gaelic and Roman times. This\n \n Celtic Church\n \n was gradually joined to the\n \n Catholic\n \n hierarchy following the 6th-century\n \n Gregorian mission\n \n to\n \n Kent\n \n led by\n \n StAugustine\n \n . The\n \n established church\n \n of England is the\n \n Church of England\n \n ,\n \n \n [217]\n \n \n which left communion with\n \n Rome\n \n in the 1530s when\n \n HenryVIII\n \n was unable to annul his divorce to\n \n the aunt\n \n of the\n \n king of Spain\n \n . The church regards itself as both Catholic and\n \n Protestant\n \n .\n \n \n [218]\n \n \n

\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n \n
\n \n Saint George\n \n is the\n \n patron saint\n \n of England\n
\n
\n
\n

\n There are\n \n High Church\n \n and\n \n Low Church\n \n traditions and some Anglicans regard themselves as\n \n Anglo-Catholics\n \n , following the\n \n Tractarian movement\n \n . The monarch of the United Kingdom is the\n \n Supreme Governor of the Church of England\n \n , which has around 26million baptised members (of whom the vast majority are not regular churchgoers). It forms part of the\n \n Anglican Communion\n \n with the\n \n Archbishop of Canterbury\n \n acting as its symbolic worldwide head.\n \n \n [219]\n \n \n Many\n \n cathedrals\n \n and parish churches are historic buildings of significant architectural importance, such as\n \n Westminster Abbey\n \n ,\n \n York Minster\n \n ,\n \n Durham Cathedral\n \n , and\n \n Salisbury Cathedral\n \n .\n

\n

\n The 2nd-largest Christian practice is the\n \n Latin Rite\n \n of the Catholic Church. Since its reintroduction after the\n \n Catholic Emancipation\n \n , the Church has organised ecclesiastically on an\n \n England and Wales\n \n basis where there are 4.5million members (most of whom are English).\n \n \n [220]\n \n \n There has been one Pope from England to date,\n \n Adrian IV\n \n ; while saints\n \n Bede\n \n and\n \n Anselm\n \n are regarded as\n \n Doctors of the Church\n \n .\n

\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n \n
\n \n Westminster Abbey\n \n is a notable example of\n \n English Gothic architecture\n \n . The\n \n coronation of the British monarch\n \n traditionally takes place at the Abbey\n
\n
\n
\n

\n A form of\n \n Protestantism\n \n known as\n \n Methodism\n \n is the third largest Christian practice and grew out of Anglicanism through\n \n John Wesley\n \n .\n \n \n [221]\n \n \n It gained popularity in the\n \n mill towns\n \n of\n \n Lancashire\n \n and\n \n Yorkshire\n \n , and amongst tin miners in\n \n Cornwall\n \n .\n \n \n [222]\n \n \n There are other\n \n non-conformist\n \n minorities, such as\n \n Baptists\n \n ,\n \n Quakers\n \n ,\n \n Congregationalists\n \n ,\n \n Unitarians\n \n and\n \n The Salvation Army\n \n .\n \n \n [223]\n \n \n

\n

\n The patron saint of England is\n \n Saint George\n \n ; his symbolic cross is included in the flag of England, as well as in the Union Flag as part of a combination.\n \n \n [224]\n \n \n There are many other English and associated saints; some of the best-known are:\n \n Cuthbert\n \n ,\n \n Edmund\n \n ,\n \n Alban\n \n ,\n \n Wilfrid\n \n ,\n \n Aidan\n \n ,\n \n Edward the Confessor\n \n ,\n \n John Fisher\n \n ,\n \n Thomas More\n \n ,\n \n Petroc\n \n ,\n \n Piran\n \n ,\n \n Margaret Clitherow\n \n and\n \n Thomas Becket\n \n . There are non-Christian religions practised. Jews have a history of a small minority on the island since 1070.\n \n \n [225]\n \n \n They were expelled from England in 1290 following the\n \n Edict of Expulsion\n \n , only to be allowed back in 1656.\n \n \n [225]\n \n \n

\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n \n
\n \n BAPS Shri Swaminarayan Mandir in London, United Kingdom\n \n is the largest\n \n Hindu temple\n \n in England.\n
\n
\n
\n

\n Especially since the 1950s, religions from the\n \n former British colonies\n \n have grown in numbers, due to immigration. Islam is the most common of these, now accounting for around 5% of the population in England.\n \n \n [226]\n \n \n \n Hinduism\n \n ,\n \n Sikhism\n \n and\n \n Buddhism\n \n are next in number, adding up to 2.8% combined,\n \n \n [226]\n \n \n introduced from India and\n \n South East Asia\n \n .\n \n \n [226]\n \n \n

\n

\n A small minority of the population practise ancient\n \n Pagan religions\n \n .\n \n Neopaganism in the United Kingdom\n \n is primarily represented by\n \n Wicca\n \n and\n \n Witchcraft religions\n \n ,\n \n Druidry\n \n , and\n \n Heathenry\n \n . According to the\n \n 2011 UK Census\n \n , there are roughly 53,172 people who identify as Pagan in England,\n \n \n [nb 5]\n \n \n and 3,448 in\n \n Wales\n \n ,\n \n \n [nb 5]\n \n \n including 11,026\n \n Wiccans\n \n in England and 740 in Wales.\n \n \n [nb 6]\n \n \n

\n

\n \n Education\n \n

\n
\n Main article:\n \n Education in England\n \n
\n
\n See also:\n \n List of universities in England\n \n
\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n \n
\n The frontage of\n \n Warwick School\n \n , one of the oldest independent schools in England\n
\n
\n
\n

\n The\n \n Department for Education\n \n is the government department responsible for issues affecting people in England up to the age of 19, including education.\n \n \n [228]\n \n \n State-run and state-funded schools are attended by approximately 93% of English schoolchildren.\n \n \n [229]\n \n \n Of these, a minority are\n \n faith schools\n \n (primarily\n \n Church of England\n \n or\n \n Roman Catholic\n \n schools). Children who are between the ages of 3 and 5 attend nursery or an\n \n Early Years Foundation Stage\n \n reception unit within a primary school. Children between the ages of 5 and 11 attend primary school, and secondary school is attended by those aged between 11 and 16. After finishing compulsory education, students take\n \n GCSE\n \n examinations. Students may then opt to continue into\n \n further education\n \n for two years.\n \n Further education colleges\n \n (particularly\n \n sixth form colleges\n \n ) often form part of a secondary school site.\n \n A-level\n \n examinations are sat by a large number of further education students, and often form the basis of an application to university.\n

\n

\n Although most English secondary schools are\n \n comprehensive\n \n , in some areas there are selective intake\n \n grammar schools\n \n , to which entrance is subject to passing the\n \n eleven-plus\n \n exam. Around 7.2% of English schoolchildren attend\n \n private schools\n \n , which are funded by private sources.\n \n \n [230]\n \n \n Standards in state schools are monitored by the\n \n Office for Standards in Education\n \n , and in private schools by the\n \n Independent Schools Inspectorate\n \n .\n \n \n [231]\n \n \n

\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n \n
\n \n Somerville College\n \n , University of Oxford\n
\n
\n
\n

\n Higher education students normally attend university from age 18 onwards, where they study for an\n \n academic degree\n \n . There are over 90universities in England, all but one of which are\n \n public institutions\n \n . The\n \n Department for Business, Innovation and Skills\n \n is the government department responsible for higher education in England.\n \n \n [232]\n \n \n Students are generally entitled to\n \n student loans\n \n to cover the cost of\n \n tuition fees\n \n and living costs.\n \n \n [nb 7]\n \n \n The first degree offered to undergraduates is the\n \n Bachelor\'s degree\n \n , which usually takes three years to complete. Students are then able to work towards a postgraduate degree, which usually takes one year, or towards a doctorate, which takes three or more years. Since the establishment of\n \n Bedford College\n \n (\n \n London\n \n ),\n \n Girton College\n \n (Cambridge) and\n \n Somerville College\n \n (Oxford) in the\n \n 19th century\n \n , women also can obtain a university degree.\n

\n

\n \n England\'s universities\n \n include some of the highest-ranked universities in the world;\n \n University of Cambridge\n \n ,\n \n University of Oxford\n \n ,\n \n Imperial College London\n \n ,\n \n University College London\n \n and\n \n King\'s College London\n \n are all ranked in the global top 30 in the 2018\n \n \n QS World University Rankings\n \n \n .\n \n \n [233]\n \n \n The\n \n London School of Economics\n \n has been described as the world\'s leading social science institution for both teaching and research.\n \n \n [234]\n \n \n The\n \n London Business School\n \n is considered one of the world\'s leading business schools and in 2010 its MBA programme was ranked best in the world by the\n \n \n Financial Times\n \n \n .\n \n \n [235]\n \n \n \n Academic degrees\n \n in England are usually split into classes: first class (1st), upper second class (2:1), lower second class (2:2), third (3rd), and unclassified.\n

\n

\n \n The King\'s School, Canterbury\n \n and\n \n King\'s School, Rochester\n \n are the oldest schools in the English-speaking world.\n \n \n [236]\n \n \n Many of England\'s most well-known schools, such as\n \n Winchester College\n \n ,\n \n Eton\n \n ,\n \n St Paul\'s School\n \n ,\n \n Harrow School\n \n and\n \n Rugby School\n \n are fee-paying institutions.\n \n \n [237]\n \n \n

\n
\n
\n

\n \n Culture\n \n

\n
\n Main article:\n \n Culture of England\n \n
\n
\n Further information:\n \n English Renaissance\n \n
\n

\n \n Architecture\n \n

\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n \n
\n A\n \n red telephone box\n \n in front of\n \n St Paul\'s Cathedral\n \n , one of the most important buildings of the\n \n English Baroque\n \n period\n
\n
\n
\n

\n Many ancient\n \n standing stone\n \n monuments were erected during the prehistoric period; amongst the best known are\n \n Stonehenge\n \n ,\n \n Devil\'s Arrows\n \n ,\n \n Rudston Monolith\n \n and\n \n Castlerigg\n \n .\n \n \n [238]\n \n \n With the introduction of\n \n Ancient Roman architecture\n \n there was a development of\n \n basilicas\n \n ,\n \n baths\n \n ,\n \n amphitheaters\n \n ,\n \n triumphal arches\n \n ,\n \n villas\n \n ,\n \n Roman temples\n \n ,\n \n Roman roads\n \n ,\n \n Roman forts\n \n ,\n \n stockades\n \n and\n \n aqueducts\n \n .\n \n \n [239]\n \n \n It was the Romans who founded the first cities and towns such as London, Bath, York, Chester and St Albans. Perhaps the best-known example is\n \n Hadrian\'s Wall\n \n stretching right across northern England.\n \n \n [239]\n \n \n Another well-preserved example is the\n \n Roman Baths\n \n at\n \n Bath, Somerset\n \n .\n \n \n [239]\n \n \n

\n

\n \n Early Medieval architecture\'s\n \n secular buildings were simple constructions mainly using timber with\n \n thatch\n \n for roofing. Ecclesiastical architecture ranged from a synthesis of\n \n Hiberno\n \n \n \n Saxon\n \n \n monasticism\n \n ,\n \n \n [240]\n \n \n \n \n [241]\n \n \n to\n \n Early Christian\n \n \n basilica\n \n and architecture characterised by pilaster-strips, blank arcading, baluster shafts and triangular headed openings. After the Norman conquest in 1066 various\n \n Castles in England\n \n were created so law lords could uphold their authority and in the north to protect from invasion. Some of the best-known medieval castles are the\n \n Tower of London\n \n ,\n \n Warwick Castle\n \n ,\n \n Durham Castle\n \n and\n \n Windsor Castle\n \n .\n \n \n [242]\n \n \n

\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n \n
\n \n Bodiam Castle\n \n is a 14th-century\n \n moated\n \n \n castle\n \n near\n \n Robertsbridge\n \n in East Sussex\n
\n
\n
\n

\n Throughout the Plantagenet era, an\n \n English Gothic architecture\n \n flourished, with prime examples including the\n \n medieval cathedrals\n \n such as\n \n Canterbury Cathedral\n \n ,\n \n Westminster Abbey\n \n and\n \n York Minster\n \n .\n \n \n [242]\n \n \n Expanding on the\n \n Norman base\n \n there was also\n \n castles\n \n ,\n \n palaces\n \n ,\n \n great houses\n \n , universities and\n \n parish churches\n \n . Medieval architecture was completed with the 16th-century\n \n Tudor style\n \n ; the four-centred arch, now known as the\n \n Tudor arch\n \n , was a defining feature as were\n \n wattle and daub\n \n houses domestically. In the aftermath of the\n \n Renaissance\n \n a form of architecture echoing classical antiquity synthesised with Christianity appeared, the\n \n English Baroque\n \n style of architect\n \n Christopher Wren\n \n being particularly championed.\n \n \n [243]\n \n \n

\n

\n \n Georgian architecture\n \n followed in a more refined style, evoking a simple Palladian form; the\n \n Royal Crescent\n \n at Bath is one of the best examples of this. With the emergence of\n \n romanticism\n \n during Victorian period, a\n \n Gothic Revival\n \n was launched. In addition to this, around the same time the Industrial Revolution paved the way for buildings such as\n \n The Crystal Palace\n \n . Since the 1930s various\n \n modernist\n \n forms have appeared whose reception is often controversial, though traditionalist resistance movements continue with support in influential places.\n \n \n [nb 8]\n \n \n

\n
\n
\n

\n \n Folklore\n \n

\n
\n Main article:\n \n English folklore\n \n
\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n \n
\n \n Robin Hood\n \n illustrated in 1912 wearing\n \n Lincoln green\n \n
\n
\n
\n

\n English folklore developed over many centuries. Some of the characters and stories are present across England, but most belong to specific regions. Common folkloric beings include\n \n pixies\n \n ,\n \n giants\n \n ,\n \n elves\n \n ,\n \n bogeymen\n \n ,\n \n trolls\n \n ,\n \n goblins\n \n and\n \n dwarves\n \n . While many legends and folk-customs are thought to be ancient, for instance the tales featuring\n \n Offa of Angel\n \n and\n \n Wayland the Smith\n \n ,\n \n \n [245]\n \n \n others date from after the Norman invasion;\n \n Robin Hood\n \n and his\n \n Merry Men\n \n of\n \n Sherwood\n \n and their battles with the\n \n Sheriff of Nottingham\n \n being, perhaps, the best known.\n \n \n [246]\n \n \n

\n

\n During the\n \n High Middle Ages\n \n tales originating from Brythonic traditions entered English folklore and developed into the\n \n Arthurian myth\n \n .\n \n \n [247]\n \n \n \n \n [248]\n \n \n \n \n [249]\n \n \n These were derived from\n \n Anglo-Norman\n \n , Welsh and French sources,\n \n \n [248]\n \n \n featuring\n \n King Arthur\n \n ,\n \n Camelot\n \n ,\n \n Excalibur\n \n ,\n \n Merlin\n \n and the\n \n Knights of the Round Table\n \n such as\n \n Lancelot\n \n . These stories are most centrally brought together within\n \n Geoffrey of Monmouth\n \n \'s\n \n \n Historia Regum Britanniae\n \n \n (\n \n History of the Kings of Britain\n \n ).\n \n \n [nb 9]\n \n \n Another early figure from\n \n British tradition\n \n ,\n \n King Cole\n \n , may have been based on a real figure from Sub-Roman Britain. Many of the tales and\n \n pseudo-histories\n \n make up part of the wider\n \n Matter of Britain\n \n , a collection of shared British folklore.\n

\n

\n Some folk figures are based on semi or actual historical people whose story has been passed down centuries;\n \n Lady Godiva\n \n for instance was said to have ridden naked on horseback through\n \n Coventry\n \n ,\n \n Hereward the Wake\n \n was a heroic English figure resisting the Norman invasion,\n \n Herne the Hunter\n \n is an\n \n equestrian\n \n ghost associated with\n \n Windsor\n \n Forest and\n \n Great Park\n \n and\n \n Mother Shipton\n \n is the archetypal witch.\n \n \n [251]\n \n \n On 5 November people make bonfires, set off\n \n fireworks\n \n and eat\n \n toffee apples\n \n in\n \n commemoration\n \n of the foiling of the\n \n Gunpowder Plot\n \n centred on\n \n Guy Fawkes\n \n . The chivalrous bandit, such as\n \n Dick Turpin\n \n , is a recurring character, while\n \n Blackbeard\n \n is the archetypal pirate. There are various national and regional folk activities, participated in to this day, such as\n \n Morris dancing\n \n ,\n \n Maypole dancing\n \n ,\n \n Rapper sword\n \n in the North East,\n \n Long Sword dance\n \n in Yorkshire,\n \n Mummers Plays\n \n ,\n \n bottle-kicking\n \n in Leicestershire, and\n \n cheese-rolling\n \n at\n \n Cooper\'s Hill\n \n .\n \n \n [252]\n \n \n There is no official national costume, but a few are well established such as the\n \n Pearly Kings and Queens\n \n associated with cockneys, the\n \n Royal Guard\n \n , the\n \n Morris costume\n \n and\n \n Beefeaters\n \n .\n \n \n [253]\n \n \n

\n

\n \n Cuisine\n \n

\n
\n Main article:\n \n English cuisine\n \n
\n \n
\n
\n
\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n Fish and chips\n \n is a very popular dish in England\n
\n
\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n Apple pie\n \n has been consumed in England since the\n \n Middle Ages\n \n
\n
\n
\n
\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n In the 1850s, Englishman\n \n Joseph Fry\n \n invented the world\'s first\n \n solid chocolate\n \n .\n \n \n [254]\n \n \n
\n
\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n Chicken tikka masala\n \n , 1971, adapted from Indian\n \n chicken tikka\n \n and called "a true British national dish."\n \n \n [255]\n \n \n
\n
\n
\n
\n
\n

\n Since the\n \n early modern period\n \n the food of England has historically been characterised by its simplicity of approach and a reliance on the high quality of natural produce.\n \n \n [256]\n \n \n During the\n \n Middle Ages\n \n and through the Renaissance period, English cuisine enjoyed an excellent reputation, though a decline began during the\n \n Industrial Revolution\n \n with the move away from the land and increasing urbanisation of the populace. The cuisine of England has, however, recently undergone a revival, which has been recognised by food critics with some good ratings in\n \n \n Restaurant\n \n \'\n \n s\n \n best restaurant in the world\n \n charts.\n \n \n [257]\n \n \n An early book of English recipes is the\n \n \n Forme of Cury\n \n \n from the royal court of\n \n Richard II\n \n .\n \n \n [258]\n \n \n

\n

\n Traditional examples of English food include the\n \n Sunday roast\n \n , featuring a\n \n roasted joint\n \n (usually beef,\n \n lamb\n \n , chicken or pork) served with assorted vegetables,\n \n Yorkshire pudding\n \n and\n \n gravy\n \n .\n \n \n [259]\n \n \n Other prominent meals include\n \n fish and chips\n \n and the\n \n full English breakfast\n \n (generally consisting of\n \n bacon\n \n ,\n \n sausages\n \n , grilled tomatoes, fried bread,\n \n black pudding\n \n ,\n \n baked beans\n \n ,\n \n mushrooms\n \n and eggs).\n \n \n [260]\n \n \n Various\n \n meat pies\n \n are consumed, such as\n \n steak and kidney pie\n \n ,\n \n steak and ale pie\n \n ,\n \n cottage pie\n \n ,\n \n pork pie\n \n (usually eaten cold)\n \n \n [259]\n \n \n and the\n \n Cornish pasty\n \n .\n

\n

\n Sausages are commonly eaten, either as\n \n bangers and mash\n \n or\n \n toad in the hole\n \n .\n \n Lancashire hotpot\n \n is a well-known stew originating in the northwest. Some of the more popular cheeses are\n \n Cheddar\n \n ,\n \n Red Leicester\n \n ,\n \n Wensleydale\n \n ,\n \n Double Gloucester\n \n and\n \n Blue Stilton\n \n . Many\n \n Anglo-Indian\n \n hybrid dishes,\n \n curries\n \n , have been created, such as\n \n chicken tikka masala\n \n and\n \n balti\n \n . Traditional English dessert dishes include\n \n apple pie\n \n or other fruit pies;\n \n spotted dick\n \n all generally served with\n \n custard\n \n ; and, more recently,\n \n sticky toffee pudding\n \n . Sweet pastries include\n \n scones\n \n (either plain or containing dried fruit) served with jam or cream, dried fruit loaves,\n \n Eccles cakes\n \n and\n \n mince pies\n \n as well as a wide range of sweet or spiced biscuits.\n

\n

\n Common non-alcoholic drinks include tea, the popularity of which was increased by\n \n Catherine of Braganza\n \n ,\n \n \n [261]\n \n \n and coffee; frequently consumed alcoholic drinks include wine,\n \n ciders\n \n and\n \n English beers\n \n , such as\n \n bitter\n \n ,\n \n mild\n \n ,\n \n stout\n \n and\n \n brown ale\n \n .\n \n \n [262]\n \n \n

\n

\n \n Visual arts\n \n

\n
\n Main article:\n \n English art\n \n
\n
\n See also:\n \n Arts Council England\n \n
\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n \n
\n \n \n The Lady of Shalott\n \n \n by\n \n John William Waterhouse\n \n in the\n \n Pre-Raphaelite\n \n style\n
\n
\n
\n

\n The earliest known examples are the prehistoric rock and\n \n cave art\n \n pieces, most prominent in\n \n North Yorkshire\n \n , Northumberland and\n \n Cumbria\n \n , but also feature further south, for example at\n \n Creswell Crags\n \n .\n \n \n [263]\n \n \n With the arrival of\n \n Roman culture\n \n in the 1st century, various forms of art such as statues, busts, glasswork and mosaics were the norm. There are numerous surviving artefacts, such as those at\n \n Lullingstone\n \n and\n \n Aldborough\n \n .\n \n \n [264]\n \n \n During the Early Middle Ages the style favoured sculpted crosses and ivories, manuscript painting, gold and enamel jewellery, demonstrating a love of intricate, interwoven designs such as in the\n \n Staffordshire Hoard\n \n discovered in 2009. Some of these blended\n \n Gaelic and Anglian\n \n styles, such as the\n \n Lindisfarne Gospels\n \n and\n \n Vespasian Psalter\n \n .\n \n \n [265]\n \n \n Later\n \n Gothic art\n \n was popular at Winchester and Canterbury, examples survive such as\n \n Benedictional of St. thelwold\n \n and\n \n Luttrell Psalter\n \n .\n \n \n [266]\n \n \n

\n

\n The Tudor era saw\n \n prominent artists\n \n as part of their court, portrait painting which would remain an enduring part of English art, was boosted by German\n \n Hans Holbein\n \n , natives such as\n \n Nicholas Hilliard\n \n built on this.\n \n \n [266]\n \n \n Under the Stuarts, Continental artists were influential especially the Flemish, examples from the period include\n \n Anthony van Dyck\n \n ,\n \n Peter Lely\n \n ,\n \n Godfrey Kneller\n \n and\n \n William Dobson\n \n .\n \n \n [266]\n \n \n The 18th century was a time of significance with the founding of the\n \n Royal Academy\n \n , a\n \n classicism\n \n based on the\n \n High Renaissance\n \n prevailed, with\n \n Thomas Gainsborough\n \n and\n \n Joshua Reynolds\n \n becoming two of England\'s most treasured artists.\n \n \n [266]\n \n \n

\n

\n The\n \n Norwich School\n \n continued the landscape tradition, while the\n \n Pre-Raphaelite Brotherhood\n \n , led by artists such as\n \n Holman Hunt\n \n ,\n \n Dante Gabriel Rossetti\n \n and\n \n John Everett Millais\n \n , revived the\n \n Early Renaissance\n \n style with their vivid and detailed style.\n \n \n [266]\n \n \n Prominent amongst 20th-century artists was\n \n Henry Moore\n \n , regarded as the voice of British sculpture, and of British modernism in general.\n \n \n [267]\n \n \n Contemporary painters include\n \n Lucian Freud\n \n , whose work\n \n \n Benefits Supervisor Sleeping\n \n \n in 2008 set a world record for sale value of a painting by a living artist.\n \n \n [268]\n \n \n

\n

\n \n \n \n Literature, poetry, and philosophy\n \n

\n
\n Main article:\n \n English literature\n \n
\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n \n
\n \n Geoffrey Chaucer\n \n was an English author, poet and philosopher, best remembered for his unfinished frame narrative\n \n \n The Canterbury Tales\n \n \n
\n
\n
\n

\n Early authors such as\n \n Bede\n \n and\n \n Alcuin\n \n wrote in Latin.\n \n \n [269]\n \n \n The period of\n \n Old English literature\n \n provided the epic poem\n \n \n Beowulf\n \n \n and the secular prose of the\n \n \n Anglo-Saxon Chronicle\n \n \n ,\n \n \n [270]\n \n \n along with Christian writings such as\n \n \n Judith\n \n \n ,\n \n Cdmon\n \n \'s\n \n \n Hymn\n \n \n and\n \n hagiographies\n \n .\n \n \n [269]\n \n \n Following the Norman conquest\n \n Latin\n \n continued amongst the educated classes, as well as an\n \n Anglo-Norman literature\n \n .\n

\n

\n \n Middle English literature\n \n emerged with\n \n Geoffrey Chaucer\n \n , author of\n \n \n The Canterbury Tales\n \n \n , along with\n \n Gower\n \n , the\n \n Pearl Poet\n \n and\n \n Langland\n \n .\n \n William of Ockham\n \n and\n \n Roger Bacon\n \n , who were\n \n Franciscans\n \n , were major philosophers of the Middle Ages.\n \n Julian of Norwich\n \n , who wrote\n \n \n Revelations of Divine Love\n \n \n , was a prominent Christian mystic. With the\n \n English Renaissance\n \n literature in the\n \n Early Modern English\n \n style appeared.\n \n William Shakespeare\n \n , whose works include\n \n \n Hamlet\n \n \n ,\n \n \n Romeo and Juliet\n \n \n ,\n \n \n Macbeth\n \n \n , and\n \n \n A Midsummer Night\'s Dream\n \n \n , remains one of the most championed authors in English literature.\n \n \n [271]\n \n \n

\n

\n \n Christopher Marlowe\n \n ,\n \n Edmund Spenser\n \n ,\n \n Philip Sydney\n \n ,\n \n Thomas Kyd\n \n ,\n \n John Donne\n \n , and\n \n Ben Jonson\n \n are other established authors of the\n \n Elizabethan age\n \n .\n \n \n [272]\n \n \n \n Francis Bacon\n \n and\n \n Thomas Hobbes\n \n wrote on\n \n empiricism\n \n and\n \n materialism\n \n , including\n \n scientific method\n \n and\n \n social contract\n \n .\n \n \n [272]\n \n \n \n Filmer\n \n wrote on the\n \n Divine Right of Kings\n \n .\n \n Marvell\n \n was the best-known poet of the\n \n Commonwealth\n \n ,\n \n \n [273]\n \n \n while\n \n John Milton\n \n authored\n \n \n Paradise Lost\n \n \n during the\n \n Restoration\n \n .\n

\n
\n \n
\n This royal throne of kings, this sceptred isle, this earth of majesty, this seat of Mars, this other Eden, demi-paradise; this fortress, built by nature for herself. This blessed plot, this earth, this realm, this England.\n
\n

\n \n \n William Shakespeare\n \n .\n \n \n [274]\n \n \n \n

\n
\n

\n Some of the most prominent philosophers of the\n \n Enlightenment\n \n were\n \n John Locke\n \n ,\n \n Thomas Paine\n \n ,\n \n Samuel Johnson\n \n and\n \n Jeremy Bentham\n \n . More radical elements were later countered by\n \n Edmund Burke\n \n who is regarded as the founder of conservatism.\n \n \n [275]\n \n \n The poet\n \n Alexander Pope\n \n with his satirical verse became well regarded. The English played a significant role in\n \n romanticism\n \n :\n \n Samuel Taylor Coleridge\n \n ,\n \n Lord Byron\n \n ,\n \n John Keats\n \n ,\n \n Mary Shelley\n \n ,\n \n Percy Bysshe Shelley\n \n ,\n \n William Blake\n \n and\n \n William Wordsworth\n \n were major figures.\n \n \n [276]\n \n \n

\n

\n In response to the\n \n Industrial Revolution\n \n , agrarian writers sought a way between\n \n liberty\n \n and tradition;\n \n William Cobbett\n \n ,\n \n G. K. Chesterton\n \n and\n \n Hilaire Belloc\n \n were main exponents, while the founder of\n \n guild socialism\n \n ,\n \n Arthur Penty\n \n , and\n \n cooperative movement\n \n advocate\n \n G. D. H. Cole\n \n are somewhat related.\n \n \n [277]\n \n \n Empiricism continued through\n \n John Stuart Mill\n \n and\n \n Bertrand Russell\n \n , while\n \n Bernard Williams\n \n was involved in\n \n analytics\n \n . Authors from around the\n \n Victorian era\n \n include\n \n Charles Dickens\n \n , the\n \n Bront sisters\n \n ,\n \n Jane Austen\n \n ,\n \n George Eliot\n \n ,\n \n Rudyard Kipling\n \n ,\n \n Thomas Hardy\n \n ,\n \n H. G. Wells\n \n and\n \n Lewis Carroll\n \n .\n \n \n [278]\n \n \n Since then England has continued to produce novelists such as\n \n George Orwell\n \n ,\n \n D. H. Lawrence\n \n ,\n \n Virginia Woolf\n \n ,\n \n C. S. Lewis\n \n ,\n \n Enid Blyton\n \n ,\n \n Aldous Huxley\n \n ,\n \n Agatha Christie\n \n ,\n \n Terry Pratchett\n \n ,\n \n J. R. R. Tolkien\n \n , and\n \n J. K. Rowling\n \n .\n \n \n [279]\n \n \n

\n The traditional\n \n folk music of England\n \n is centuries old and has contributed to several genres prominently; mostly\n \n sea shanties\n \n ,\n \n jigs\n \n ,\n \n hornpipes\n \n and\n \n dance music\n \n . It has its own distinct variations and regional peculiarities.\n \n Wynkyn de Worde\n \n printed ballads of Robin Hood from the 16th century are an important artefact, as are\n \n John Playford\n \n \'s\n \n \n The Dancing Master\n \n \n and\n \n Robert Harley\'s\n \n \n \n Roxburghe Ballads\n \n \n collections.\n \n \n [280]\n \n \n Some of the best-known songs are\n \n \n Greensleeves\n \n \n ,\n \n \n Pastime with Good Company\n \n \n ,\n \n \n Maggie May\n \n \n and\n \n \n Spanish Ladies\n \n \n amongst others. Many\n \n nursery rhymes\n \n are of English origin such as\n \n \n Twinkle Twinkle Little Star\n \n \n ,\n \n \n Roses are red\n \n \n ,\n \n \n Jack and Jill\n \n \n ,\n \n \n London Bridge Is Falling Down\n \n ,\n \n The Grand Old Duke of York\n \n ,\n \n Hey Diddle Diddle\n \n \n and\n \n \n Humpty Dumpty\n \n \n .\n \n \n [281]\n \n \n Traditional English Christmas carols include "\n \n We Wish You a Merry Christmas\n \n ", "\n \n The First Noel\n \n " and "\n \n God Rest You Merry, Gentlemen\n \n ".\n \n \n [282]\n \n \n
