\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n \n
\n \n The Beatles\n \n are the most commercially successful and critically acclaimed band in popular music.\n \n \n [283]\n \n \n \n \n [284]\n \n \n \n \n [285]\n \n \n
\n
\n
\n

\n Early English composers in classical music include Renaissance artists\n \n Thomas Tallis\n \n and\n \n William Byrd\n \n , followed up by\n \n Henry Purcell\n \n from the\n \n Baroque period\n \n . German-born\n \n George Frideric Handel\n \n became a British subject\n \n \n [286]\n \n \n and spent most of his composing life in London, creating some of the most well-known works of classical music,\n \n \n The Messiah\n \n \n ,\n \n \n Water Music\n \n \n , and\n \n \n Music for the Royal Fireworks\n \n \n . One of his four\n \n Coronation Anthems\n \n ,\n \n \n Zadok the Priest\n \n \n , composed for the coronation of\n \n George II\n \n , has been performed at every subsequent\n \n British coronation\n \n , traditionally during the sovereign\'s anointing. There was a revival in the profile of composers from England in the 20th century led by\n \n Edward Elgar\n \n ,\n \n Benjamin Britten\n \n ,\n \n Frederick Delius\n \n ,\n \n Gustav Holst\n \n ,\n \n Ralph Vaughan Williams\n \n and others.\n \n \n [287]\n \n \n Present-day composers from England include\n \n Michael Nyman\n \n , best known for\n \n \n The Piano\n \n \n , and\n \n Andrew Lloyd Webber\n \n , whose musicals have achieved enormous success in the\n \n West End\n \n and worldwide.\n \n \n [288]\n \n \n

\n

\n In the field of\n \n popular music\n \n , many English bands and solo artists have been cited as the most influential and best-selling musicians of all time. Acts such as\n \n The Beatles\n \n ,\n \n Led Zeppelin\n \n ,\n \n Pink Floyd\n \n ,\n \n Elton John\n \n ,\n \n Queen\n \n ,\n \n Rod Stewart\n \n and\n \n The Rolling Stones\n \n are among the highest selling recording artists in the world.\n \n \n [289]\n \n \n Many musical genres have origins in (or strong associations with) England, such as\n \n British invasion\n \n ,\n \n progressive rock\n \n ,\n \n hard rock\n \n ,\n \n Mod\n \n ,\n \n glam rock\n \n ,\n \n heavy metal\n \n ,\n \n Britpop\n \n ,\n \n indie rock\n \n ,\n \n gothic rock\n \n ,\n \n shoegazing\n \n ,\n \n acid house\n \n ,\n \n garage\n \n ,\n \n trip hop\n \n ,\n \n drum and bass\n \n and\n \n dubstep\n \n .\n \n \n [290]\n \n \n

\n

\n Large outdoor\n \n music festivals\n \n in the summer and autumn are popular, such as\n \n Glastonbury\n \n ,\n \n V Festival\n \n , and the\n \n Reading and Leeds Festivals\n \n . The most prominent\n \n opera house\n \n in England is the\n \n Royal Opera House\n \n at\n \n Covent Garden\n \n .\n \n \n [291]\n \n \n \n The Proms\n \n a season of\n \n orchestral\n \n classical concerts held primarily at the\n \n Royal Albert Hall\n \n in London is a major cultural event in the English calendar, and takes place yearly.\n \n \n [291]\n \n \n \n The Royal Ballet\n \n is one of the world\'s foremost classical ballet companies, its reputation built on two prominent figures of 20th-century dance,\n \n \n prima ballerina\n \n \n \n Margot Fonteyn\n \n and choreographer\n \n Frederick Ashton\n \n .\n

\n

\n \n Cinema\n \n

\n
\n See also:\n \n Cinema of the United Kingdom\n \n
\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n \n
\n \n Ridley Scott\n \n was among a group of English filmmakers, including\n \n Tony Scott\n \n ,\n \n Alan Parker\n \n ,\n \n Hugh Hudson\n \n and\n \n Adrian Lyne\n \n , who emerged from making 1970s UK television commercials.\n \n \n [292]\n \n \n
\n
\n
\n

\n England (and the UK as a whole) has had a considerable influence on the history of the cinema, producing some of the greatest actors, directors and motion pictures of all time, including\n \n Alfred Hitchcock\n \n ,\n \n Charlie Chaplin\n \n ,\n \n David Lean\n \n ,\n \n Laurence Olivier\n \n ,\n \n Vivien Leigh\n \n ,\n \n John Gielgud\n \n ,\n \n Peter Sellers\n \n ,\n \n Julie Andrews\n \n ,\n \n Michael Caine\n \n ,\n \n Gary Oldman\n \n ,\n \n Helen Mirren\n \n ,\n \n Kate Winslet\n \n and\n \n Daniel Day-Lewis\n \n . Hitchcock and Lean are among the most critically acclaimed filmmakers.\n \n \n [293]\n \n \n Hitchcock\'s first thriller,\n \n \n The Lodger: A Story of the London Fog\n \n \n (1926), helped shape the\n \n thriller\n \n genre in film, while his 1929 film,\n \n \n Blackmail\n \n \n , is often regarded as the first British\n \n sound\n \n feature film.\n \n \n [294]\n \n \n

\n

\n Major film studios in England include\n \n Pinewood\n \n ,\n \n Elstree\n \n and\n \n Shepperton\n \n . Some of the most commercially successful films of all time have been produced in England, including two of the\n \n highest-grossing film franchises\n \n (\n \n \n Harry Potter\n \n \n and\n \n \n James Bond\n \n \n ).\n \n \n [295]\n \n \n \n Ealing Studios\n \n in London has a claim to being the oldest continuously working film studio in the world.\n \n \n [296]\n \n \n Famous for recording many motion picture\n \n film scores\n \n , the\n \n London Symphony Orchestra\n \n first performed film music in 1935.\n \n \n [297]\n \n \n

\n

\n The\n \n BFI Top 100 British films\n \n includes\n \n \n Monty Python\'s Life of Brian\n \n \n (1979), a film regularly voted the funniest of all time by the UK public.\n \n \n [298]\n \n \n English producers are also active in\n \n international co-productions\n \n and English actors, directors and crew feature regularly in American films. The UK film council ranked\n \n David Yates\n \n ,\n \n Christopher Nolan\n \n ,\n \n Mike Newell\n \n ,\n \n Ridley Scott\n \n and\n \n Paul Greengrass\n \n the five most commercially successful English directors since 2001.\n \n \n [299]\n \n \n Other contemporary English directors include\n \n Sam Mendes\n \n ,\n \n Guy Ritchie\n \n and\n \n Steve McQueen\n \n . Current actors include\n \n Tom Hardy\n \n ,\n \n Daniel Craig\n \n ,\n \n Benedict Cumberbatch\n \n and\n \n Emma Watson\n \n . Acclaimed for his motion capture work,\n \n Andy Serkis\n \n opened\n \n The Imaginarium Studios\n \n in London in 2011.\n \n \n [300]\n \n \n The visual effects company\n \n Framestore\n \n in London has produced some of the most critically acclaimed special effects in modern film.\n \n \n [301]\n \n \n Many successful Hollywood films have been based on English people,\n \n stories\n \n or events. The\n \n \'English Cycle\'\n \n of Disney animated films include\n \n \n Alice in Wonderland\n \n \n ,\n \n \n The Jungle Book\n \n \n and\n \n \n Winnie the Pooh\n \n \n .\n \n \n [302]\n \n \n

\n

\n \n \n \n Museums, libraries, and galleries\n \n

\n
\n Further information:\n \n List of museums in England\n \n
\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n \n
\n The\n \n Natural History Museum\n \n in London\n
\n
\n
\n

\n \n English Heritage\n \n is a governmental body with a broad remit of managing the historic sites, artefacts and environments of England. It is currently sponsored by the\n \n Department for Culture, Media and Sport\n \n . The charity\n \n National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty\n \n holds a contrasting role. 17 of the 25 United Kingdom UNESCO\n \n World Heritage Sites\n \n fall within England.\n \n \n [303]\n \n \n Some of the best-known of these are:\n \n Hadrian\'s Wall\n \n ,\n \n Stonehenge, Avebury and Associated Sites\n \n ,\n \n Tower of London\n \n ,\n \n Jurassic Coast\n \n ,\n \n Saltaire\n \n ,\n \n Ironbridge Gorge\n \n ,\n \n Studley Royal Park\n \n and various others.\n \n \n [304]\n \n \n

\n

\n There are many museums in England, but perhaps the most notable is London\'s\n \n British Museum\n \n . Its collection of more than seven million objects\n \n \n [305]\n \n \n is one of the largest and most comprehensive in the world,\n \n \n [306]\n \n \n sourced from every continent, illustrating and documenting the story of human culture from its beginning to the present. The\n \n British Library\n \n in London is the\n \n national library\n \n and is one of the world\'s largest\n \n research libraries\n \n , holding over 150million items in all known languages and formats; including around 25million books.\n \n \n [307]\n \n \n The most senior art gallery is the\n \n National Gallery\n \n in\n \n Trafalgar Square\n \n , which houses a collection of over 2,300 paintings dating from the mid-13th century to 1900.\n \n \n [308]\n \n \n The\n \n Tate\n \n galleries house the national collections of British and international modern art; they also host the famously controversial\n \n Turner Prize\n \n .\n \n \n [309]\n \n \n

\n

\n \n Sports\n \n

\n
\n Main article:\n \n Sport in England\n \n
\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n \n
\n Queen\n \n Elizabeth II\n \n presenting the\n \n World Cup trophy\n \n to 1966 World Cup winning England captain\n \n Bobby Moore\n \n
\n
\n
\n

\n England has a strong sporting heritage, and during the 19th century codified many sports that are now played around the world. Sports originating in England include\n \n association football\n \n ,\n \n \n [310]\n \n \n \n cricket\n \n ,\n \n rugby union\n \n ,\n \n rugby league\n \n ,\n \n tennis\n \n ,\n \n boxing\n \n , badminton,\n \n squash\n \n ,\n \n \n [311]\n \n \n \n rounders\n \n ,\n \n \n [312]\n \n \n \n hockey\n \n ,\n \n snooker\n \n ,\n \n billiards\n \n ,\n \n darts\n \n , table tennis,\n \n bowls\n \n ,\n \n netball\n \n ,\n \n thoroughbred\n \n horseracing,\n \n greyhound racing\n \n and\n \n fox hunting\n \n . It has helped the development of\n \n golf\n \n , sailing and\n \n Formula One\n \n .\n

\n

\n Football is the\n \n most popular\n \n of these sports. The\n \n England national football team\n \n , whose home venue is\n \n Wembley Stadium\n \n , played\n \n Scotland\n \n in the first ever international football match in 1872.\n \n \n [313]\n \n \n Referred to as the "home of football" by\n \n FIFA\n \n , England hosted the\n \n 1966 FIFA World Cup\n \n , and won the tournament by defeating\n \n West Germany\n \n 42 in the\n \n final\n \n , with\n \n Geoff Hurst\n \n scoring a\n \n hat-trick\n \n .\n \n \n [314]\n \n \n With a British television audience peak of 32.30million viewers, the final is the\n \n most watched television event ever\n \n in the UK.\n \n \n [315]\n \n \n

\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n \n
\n \n Wembley Stadium\n \n , home of the\n \n England football team\n \n , has a 90,000 capacity. It is the biggest stadium in the UK\n
\n
\n
\n

\n At club level, England is recognised by FIFA as the birthplace of club football, due to\n \n Sheffield F.C.\n \n founded in 1857 being the world\'s oldest club.\n \n \n [310]\n \n \n \n The Football Association\n \n is the oldest governing body in the sport, with the\n \n rules\n \n of football first drafted in 1863 by\n \n Ebenezer Cobb Morley\n \n .\n \n \n [316]\n \n \n The\n \n FA Cup\n \n and\n \n The Football League\n \n were the first cup and league competitions respectively. In the modern day, the\n \n Premier League\n \n is the world\'s most-watched football league,\n \n \n [317]\n \n \n most lucrative,\n \n \n [318]\n \n \n and amongst the elite.\n \n \n [319]\n \n \n

\n

\n As is the case throughout the UK, football in England is notable for the rivalries between clubs and the passion of the supporters, which includes a tradition of football chants.\n \n \n [320]\n \n \n \n \n [321]\n \n \n The\n \n European Cup\n \n (now\n \n UEFA Champions League\n \n ) has been won by several English clubs.\n \n \n [322]\n \n \n The most successful English football team in the European Cup/UEFA Champions League is\n \n Liverpool Football Club\n \n who have won the competition on five occasions.\n \n \n [323]\n \n \n Other English success has come from\n \n Manchester United Football Club\n \n , winning the competition on 3 occasions;\n \n Nottingham Forest Football Club\n \n on 2 occasions,\n \n Aston Villa Football Club\n \n and\n \n Chelsea Football Club\n \n have both won the trophy once.\n \n \n [324]\n \n \n

\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n \n
\n \n England\n \n playing\n \n Australia\n \n at\n \n Lord\'s Cricket Ground\n \n in the\n \n 2009 Ashes series\n \n
\n
\n
\n

\n \n Cricket\n \n is generally thought to have been developed in the early medieval period among the farming and metalworking communities of the\n \n Weald\n \n .\n \n \n [325]\n \n \n The\n \n England cricket team\n \n is a composite England and Wales, team. One of the game\'s top rivalries is\n \n The Ashes\n \n series between England and\n \n Australia\n \n , contested since 1882. The climax of the\n \n 2005 Ashes\n \n was viewed by 7.4million as it was available on terrestrial television.\n \n \n [326]\n \n \n England has hosted four\n \n Cricket World Cups\n \n (1975, 1979, 1983, 1999) and will host the\n \n 2019 edition\n \n , but never won the tournament, reaching the final 3 times. However they have hosted the\n \n ICC World Twenty20\n \n in\n \n 2009\n \n , winning this format in 2010 beating rivals Australia in the final. In the domestic competition, the\n \n County Championship\n \n ,\n \n Yorkshire\n \n are by far the most successful club having won the competition 32times outright and sharing it on 1 other occasion.\n \n \n [327]\n \n \n \n Lord\'s Cricket Ground\n \n situated in London is sometimes referred to as the "Mecca of Cricket".\n \n \n [328]\n \n \n

\n

\n \n William Penny Brookes\n \n was prominent in organising the format for the modern\n \n Olympic Games\n \n . In 1994, then President of the\n \n IOC\n \n ,\n \n Juan Antonio Samaranch\n \n , laid a wreath on Brooke\'s grave, and said, "I came to pay homage and tribute to Dr Brookes, who really was the founder of the modern Olympic Games".\n \n \n [329]\n \n \n London has hosted the\n \n Summer Olympic Games\n \n three times, in\n \n 1908\n \n ,\n \n 1948\n \n , and\n \n 2012\n \n . England competes in the\n \n Commonwealth Games\n \n , held every four years.\n \n Sport England\n \n is the governing body responsible for distributing funds and providing strategic guidance for sporting activity in England.\n

\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n \n
\n The\n \n England rugby union team\n \n during their victory parade after winning the\n \n 2003 Rugby World Cup\n \n
\n
\n
\n

\n \n Rugby union\n \n originated in\n \n Rugby School\n \n , Warwickshire in the early 19th century.\n \n \n [330]\n \n \n The\n \n England rugby union team\n \n won the\n \n 2003 Rugby World Cup\n \n , with\n \n Jonny Wilkinson\n \n scoring the winning\n \n drop goal\n \n in the last minute of extra time against Australia. England was one of the host nations of the competition in the\n \n 1991 Rugby World Cup\n \n and also hosted the\n \n 2015 Rugby World Cup\n \n .\n \n \n [331]\n \n \n The top level of club participation is the\n \n English Premiership\n \n .\n \n Leicester Tigers\n \n ,\n \n London Wasps\n \n ,\n \n Bath Rugby\n \n and\n \n Northampton Saints\n \n have had success in the Europe-wide\n \n Heineken Cup\n \n .\n

\n

\n \n Rugby league\n \n was born in\n \n Huddersfield\n \n in 1895. Since 2008, the\n \n England national rugby league team\n \n has been a full test nation in lieu of the\n \n Great Britain national rugby league team\n \n , which won three\n \n World Cups\n \n but is now retired. Club sides play in\n \n Super League\n \n , the present-day embodiment of the\n \n Rugby Football League Championship\n \n . Rugby League is most popular among towns in the northern English counties of\n \n Lancashire\n \n , Yorkshire and\n \n Cumbria\n \n .\n \n \n [332]\n \n \n All eleven English clubs in Super League are based in the north of England. Some of the most successful clubs include\n \n Wigan Warriors\n \n ,\n \n Hull F.C.\n \n \n St. Helens\n \n ,\n \n Leeds Rhinos\n \n and\n \n Huddersfield Giants\n \n ; the former three have all won the\n \n World Club Challenge\n \n previously.\n

\n

\n \n Golf\n \n has been prominent in England; due in part to its cultural and geographical ties to Scotland, the\n \n home of Golf\n \n .\n \n \n [333]\n \n \n There are both professional tours for men and women, in two main tours: the\n \n PGA\n \n and the\n \n European Tour\n \n . England has produced grand slam winners:\n \n Cyril Walker\n \n ,\n \n Tony Jacklin\n \n ,\n \n Nick Faldo\n \n , and\n \n Justin Rose\n \n in the men\'s and\n \n Laura Davies\n \n ,\n \n Alison Nicholas\n \n , and\n \n Karen Stupples\n \n in the women\'s. The world\'s oldest golf tournament, and golf\'s first major is\n \n The Open Championship\n \n , played both in England and Scotland. The biennial golf competition, the\n \n Ryder Cup\n \n , is named after English businessman\n \n Samuel Ryder\n \n who sponsored the event and donated the trophy.\n \n \n [334]\n \n \n Nick Faldo is the most successful Ryder Cup player ever, having won the most points (25) of any player on either the European or US teams.\n \n \n [335]\n \n \n

\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n \n
\n \n Centre Court\n \n at\n \n Wimbledon\n \n . First played in 1877, the Wimbledon Championships is the oldest tennis tournament in the world.\n \n \n [336]\n \n \n
\n
\n
\n

\n \n Tennis\n \n was created in Birmingham in the late 19th century, and\n \n the Wimbledon Championships\n \n is the oldest tennis tournament in the world, and widely considered the most prestigious.\n \n \n [337]\n \n \n \n \n [338]\n \n \n Wimbledon is a tournament that has a major place in the British cultural calendar.\n \n Fred Perry\n \n was the last Englishman to win Wimbledon in 1936. He was the first player to win all four\n \n Grand Slam\n \n singles titles\n \n \n [339]\n \n \n and helped lead the\n \n Great Britain\n \n team to four\n \n Davis Cup\n \n wins. English women who have won Wimbledon include:\n \n Ann Haydon Jones\n \n in 1969 and\n \n Virginia Wade\n \n in 1977.\n

\n

\n In\n \n boxing\n \n , under the\n \n Marquess of Queensberry Rules\n \n , England has produced many world champions across the weight divisions internationally recognised by the governing bodies. World champions include\n \n Bob Fitzsimmons\n \n ,\n \n Ted "Kid" Lewis\n \n ,\n \n Randolph Turpin\n \n ,\n \n Nigel Benn\n \n ,\n \n Chris Eubank\n \n ,\n \n Frank Bruno\n \n ,\n \n Lennox Lewis\n \n ,\n \n Ricky Hatton\n \n ,\n \n Naseem Hamed\n \n ,\n \n Amir Khan\n \n ,\n \n Carl Froch\n \n , and\n \n David Haye\n \n .\n \n \n [340]\n \n \n In women\'s boxing,\n \n Nicola Adams\n \n became the world\'s first woman to win an Olympic boxing Gold medal at the\n \n 2012 Summer Olympics\n \n .\n

\n

\n Originating in 17th and 18th-century England, the\n \n thoroughbred\n \n is a horse breed best known for its use in\n \n horse racing\n \n . The\n \n National Hunt\n \n horse race the\n \n Grand National\n \n , is held annually at\n \n Aintree Racecourse\n \n in early April. It is the most watched horse race in the UK, attracting casual observers, and three-time winner\n \n Red Rum\n \n is the most successful racehorse in the event\'s history.\n \n \n [341]\n \n \n Red Rum is also the best-known racehorse in the country.\n \n \n [342]\n \n \n

\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n \n
\n Former\n \n Formula One\n \n world champion\n \n Nigel Mansell\n \n driving at\n \n Silverstone\n \n in 1990. The circuit hosted the\n \n first ever Formula One race\n \n in 1950\n
\n
\n
\n

\n The\n \n 1950 British Grand Prix\n \n at\n \n Silverstone\n \n was the first race in the newly created\n \n Formula One World Championship\n \n .\n \n \n [343]\n \n \n Since then, England has produced some of the greatest drivers in the sport, including;\n \n John Surtees\n \n ,\n \n Stirling Moss\n \n ,\n \n Graham Hill\n \n (only driver to have won the\n \n Triple Crown\n \n ),\n \n Nigel Mansell\n \n (only man to hold F1 and IndyCar titles at the same time),\n \n Damon Hill\n \n ,\n \n Lewis Hamilton\n \n and\n \n Jenson Button\n \n .\n \n \n [344]\n \n \n It has manufactured some of the most technically advanced racing cars, and many of today\'s racing companies choose England as their base of operations for its engineering knowledge and organisation.\n \n McLaren Automotive\n \n ,\n \n Williams F1\n \n ,\n \n Team Lotus\n \n ,\n \n Honda\n \n ,\n \n Brawn GP\n \n ,\n \n Benetton\n \n ,\n \n Renault\n \n , and\n \n Red Bull Racing\n \n are all, or have been, located in the south of England. England also has a rich heritage in\n \n Grand Prix motorcycle racing\n \n , the premier championship of motorcycle\n \n road racing\n \n , and produced several World Champions across all the various class of motorcycle:\n \n Mike Hailwood\n \n ,\n \n John Surtees\n \n ,\n \n Phil Read\n \n ,\n \n Geoff Duke\n \n , and\n \n Barry Sheene\n \n .\n

\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n \n
\n \n Mo Farah\n \n is the most successful British track athlete in modern Olympic Games history, winning the 5000m and 10,000m events at two Olympic Games\n
\n
\n
\n

\n \n Darts\n \n is a widely popular sport in England; a professional competitive sport, darts is a traditional\n \n pub game\n \n . The sport is governed by the\n \n World Darts Federation\n \n , one of its member organisations is the\n \n BDO\n \n , which annually stages the Lakeside World Professional Championship, the other being the\n \n Professional Darts Corporation\n \n (PDC), which runs its own world championship at\n \n Alexandra Palace\n \n in London.\n \n Phil Taylor\n \n is widely regarded as the best darts player of all time, having won 187 professional tournaments, and a record 16\n \n World Championships\n \n .\n \n \n [345]\n \n \n \n \n [346]\n \n \n \n Trina Gulliver\n \n is the ten-time Women\'s World Professional Darts Champion of the\n \n British Darts Organisation\n \n . Another popular sport commonly associated with pub games is\n \n Snooker\n \n , and England has produced several world champions, including\n \n Steve Davis\n \n and\n \n Ronnie O\'Sullivan\n \n .\n

\n

\n The English are keen sailors and enjoy competitive\n \n sailing\n \n ; founding and winning some of the worlds most famous and respected international competitive tournaments across the various race formats, including the\n \n match race\n \n , a regatta, and the\n \n America\'s Cup\n \n . England has produced some of the world\'s greatest sailors, including\n \n Francis Chichester\n \n ,\n \n Herbert Hasler\n \n ,\n \n John Ridgway\n \n ,\n \n Robin Knox-Johnston\n \n ,\n \n Ellen MacArthur\n \n ,\n \n Mike Golding\n \n ,\n \n Paul Goodison\n \n , and the most successful Olympic sailor ever\n \n Ben Ainslie\n \n .\n \n \n [347]\n \n \n

\n

\n \n National symbols\n \n

\n
\n Main article:\n \n National symbols of England\n \n
\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n \n
\n The\n \n Royal Arms of England\n \n
\n
\n
\n

\n The St George\'s Cross has been the national\n \n flag of England\n \n since the 13th century. Originally the flag was used by the maritime\n \n Republic of Genoa\n \n . The English monarch paid a tribute to the\n \n Doge of Genoa\n \n from 1190 onwards so that English ships could fly the flag as a means of protection when entering the Mediterranean.\nA red cross was a symbol for many\n \n Crusaders\n \n in the 12th and 13th centuries. It became associated with\n \n Saint George\n \n , along with countries and cities, which claimed him as their\n \n patron saint\n \n and used his cross as a banner.\n \n \n [348]\n \n \n Since 1606 the St George\'s Cross has formed part of the design of the\n \n Union Flag\n \n , a Pan-British flag designed by King\n \n James I\n \n .\n \n \n [224]\n \n \n During the\n \n English Civil War\n \n and\n \n Interregnum\n \n , the\n \n New Model Army\'s\n \n standards and the\n \n Commonwealth\'s\n \n \n Great Seal\n \n both incorporated the flag of Saint George.\n \n \n [349]\n \n \n \n \n [350]\n \n \n

\n
\n
\n \n \n \n
\n
\n \n \n
\n The\n \n Tudor rose\n \n , England\'s\n \n national floral emblem\n \n .\n
\n
\n
\n

\n There are numerous other symbols and symbolic artefacts, both official and unofficial, including the\n \n Tudor rose\n \n , the nation\'s\n \n floral emblem\n \n , and the Three Lions featured on the\n \n Royal Arms of England\n \n . The Tudor rose was adopted as a national emblem of England around the time of the\n \n Wars of the Roses\n \n as a symbol of peace.\n \n \n [351]\n \n \n It is a\n \n syncretic\n \n symbol in that it merged the white rose of the\n \n Yorkists\n \n and the red rose of the\n \n Lancastrians\n \n cadet branches of the\n \n Plantagenets\n \n who went to war over control of the nation. It is also known as the\n \n Rose of England\n \n .\n \n \n [352]\n \n \n The\n \n oak\n \n tree is a symbol of England, representing strength and endurance. The\n \n Royal Oak\n \n symbol and\n \n Oak Apple Day\n \n commemorate the escape of King\n \n Charles II\n \n from the grasp of the parliamentarians after his father\'s execution: he hid in an oak tree to avoid detection before safely reaching exile.\n

\n

\n The Royal Arms of England, a national\n \n coat of arms\n \n featuring three lions, originated with its adoption by\n \n Richard the Lionheart\n \n in 1198. It is\n \n blazoned\n \n as\n \n gules, three lions passant guardant or\n \n and it provides one of the most prominent symbols of England; it is similar to the traditional arms of\n \n Normandy\n \n . England does not have an official designated national anthem, as the United Kingdom as a whole has\n \n \n God Save the Queen\n \n \n . However, the following are often considered unofficial English national anthems:\n \n \n Jerusalem\n \n \n ,\n \n \n Land of Hope and Glory\n \n \n (used for England during the\n \n 2002 Commonwealth Games\n \n ),\n \n \n [353]\n \n \n and\n \n \n I Vow to Thee, My Country\n \n \n . England\'s\n \n National Day\n \n is 23 April which is\n \n St George\'s Day\n \n : St George is the patron saint of England.\n \n \n [354]\n \n \n

\n \n Notes\n \n

    \n
  1. \n \n \n \n ^\n \n \n \n \n According to the\n \n European Statistical Agency\n \n , London is the largest\n \n Larger Urban Zone\n \n in the EU, a measure of metropolitan area which comprises a city\'s urban core as well as its surrounding commuting zone. London\'s\n \n municipal population is also the largest in the EU\n \n .\n \n
    2. \n
  2. \n \n \n \n ^\n \n \n \n \n As\n \n Roger Scruton\n \n explains, "The Reformation must not be confused with the changes introduced into the Church of England during the \'Reformation Parliament\' of 152936, which were of a political rather than a religious nature, designed to unite the secular and religious sources of authority within a single sovereign power: the Anglican Church did not make substantial change in doctrine until later."\n \n \n [61]\n \n \n \n
    3. \n
  3. \n \n \n \n ^\n \n \n \n \n Figure of 550,000 military deaths is for England and Wales\n \n \n [82]\n \n \n \n
    4. \n
  4. \n \n \n \n ^\n \n \n \n \n For instance, in 1980 around 50million\n \n Americans\n \n claimed\n \n English ancestry\n \n .\n \n \n [181]\n \n \n In Canada there are around 6.5million\n \n Canadians\n \n who claim\n \n English ancestry\n \n .\n \n \n [182]\n \n \n Around 70% of\n \n Australians\n \n in 1999 denoted their origins as\n \n Anglo-Celtic\n \n , a category which includes all peoples from Great Britain and Ireland.\n \n \n [183]\n \n \n Chileans of\n \n English descent\n \n are somewhat of an anomaly in that\n \n Chile\n \n itself was never part of the British Empire, but today there are around 420,000 people of English origins living there.\n \n \n [184]\n \n \n \n
    5. \n
  5. \n \n ^\n \n \n \n \n a\n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n b\n \n \n \n \n \n \n People who strictly identified as "Pagan". Other Pagan paths, such as Wicca or Druidism, have not been included in this number.\n \n \n [227]\n \n \n \n
    6. \n
  6. \n \n \n \n ^\n \n \n \n \n People who strictly identified as "Wiccan". Other Pagan paths, such as Druidism, and general "Pagan" have not been included in this number.\n \n \n [227]\n \n \n \n
    7. \n
  7. \n \n \n \n ^\n \n \n \n \n Students attending English universities now have to pay tuition fees towards the cost of their education, as do English students who choose to attend university in Scotland. Scottish students attending Scottish universities have their fees paid by the devolved Scottish Parliament.\n \n \n [97]\n \n \n \n
    8. \n
  8. \n \n \n \n ^\n \n \n \n \n While people such as\n \n Norman Foster\n \n and\n \n Richard Rogers\n \n represent the modernist movement,\n \n Prince Charles\n \n since the 1980s has voiced strong views against it in favour of traditional architecture and put his ideas into practice at his\n \n Poundbury\n \n development in Dorset.\n \n \n [244]\n \n \n Architects like\n \n Raymond Erith\n \n ,\n \n Francis Johnson\n \n and\n \n Quinlan Terry\n \n continued to practise in the classical style.\n \n
    9. \n
  9. \n \n \n \n ^\n \n \n \n \n These tales may have come to prominence, at least in part, as an attempt by the Norman ruling elite to legitimise their rule of the British Isles, finding\n \n Anglo-Saxon\n \n history ill-suited to the task during an era when members of the deposed\n \n House of Wessex\n \n , especially\n \n Edgar the theling\n \n and his nephews of the Scottish\n \n House of Dunkeld\n \n , were still active in the isles.\n \n \n [248]\n \n \n \n \n [250]\n \n \n Also\n \n Michael Wood\n \n explains; "Over the centuries the figure of Arthur became a symbol of British history a way of explaining the matter of Britain, the relationship between the Saxons and the Celts, and a way of exorcising ghosts and healing the wounds of the past."\n \n \n [247]\n \n \n \n

  218. \n \n \n \n ^\n \n \n \n \n \n \n "In depth history of the Church of England"\n \n . Church of England\n \n . Retrieved\n \n 25 January\n \n 2017\n \n .\n \n The religious settlement that eventually emerged in the reign of Elizabeth gave the Church of England the distinctive identity that it has retained to this day. It resulted in a Church that consciously retained a large amount of continuity with the Church of the Patristic and Medieval periods in terms of its use of the catholic creeds, its pattern of ministry, its buildings and aspects of its liturgy, but which also embodied Protestant insights in its theology and in the overall shape of its liturgical practice. The way that this is often expressed is by saying that the Church of England is both \'catholic and reformed.\'\n \n \n \n \n \n \n
